2137    def _get_set_block_names(self, obj_type: ObjectType):
2138        """
2139        Returns a list of names for objects of a given type.
2140        :param obj_type: type of object
2141        :return: a list of names
2142        """
2143        names = []
2144        if obj_type == NODESET:
2145            try:
2146                names = self.data.variables[VAR_NS_NAMES]
2147            except KeyError:
2148                warnings.warn("This database does not contain node set names.")
2149        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
2150            try:
2151                names = self.data.variables[VAR_SS_NAMES]
2152            except KeyError:
2153                warnings.warn("This database does not contain side set names.")
2154        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
2155            try:
2156                names = self.data.variables[VAR_EB_NAMES]
2157            except KeyError:
2158                warnings.warn("This database does not contain element block names.")
2159        else:
2160            raise ValueError("{} is not a valid set/block type!".format(obj_type))
2161        result = numpy.empty([len(names)], self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2162        for i in range(len(names)):
2163            result[i] = util.lineparse(names[i])
2164        return result
2165
2166    def get_elem_block_names(self):
2167        """Returns an array containing the names of element blocks in this database."""
2168        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
2169            return self.ledger.get_elem_block_names()
2170        return self._get_set_block_names(ELEMBLOCK)
2171
2172    def get_elem_block_name(self, obj_id):
2173        """Returns the name of the given element block."""
2174        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
2175            return self.ledger.get_elem_block_name(obj_id)
2176        
2177        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
2178        names = self._get_set_block_names(ELEMBLOCK)
2179
2180        if len(names) > 0:
2181            return names[internal_id - 1]
2182        else:
2183            return None

2222    def _int_get_num_elem_attrib(self, internal_id):
2223        """
2224        Returns the number of attributes in the element block with given internal ID.
2225
2226        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
2227        """
2228        # Some databases don't have attributes
2229        if (DIM_NUM_ATT_IN_BLK % internal_id) in self.data.dimensions:
2230            num = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_ATT_IN_BLK % internal_id].size
2231        else:
2232            # No need to warn. If there are no attributes, the number is 0...
2233            num = 0
2234        return num
2235
2236    def _int_get_partial_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, internal_id, start, count):
2237        """
2238        Returns a partial list of all attributes for the element block with given ID.
2239
2240        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2241
2242        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY
2243
2244        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
2245        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
2246        :param start: element start index (1-based)
2247        :param count: number of elements
2248        :return: array containing the selected part of the attribute list
2249        """
2250        if start < 1:
2251            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2252        if count < 0:
2253            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2254        varname = VAR_ELEM_ATTRIB % internal_id
2255        if varname in self.data.variables:
2256            result = self.data.variables[varname][start - 1:start + count - 1, :]
2257        else:
2258            result = []
2259            warnings.warn("Element block {} has no attributes.".format(obj_id))
2260        return result
2261
2262    def _int_get_partial_one_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, internal_id, attrib_index, start, count):
2263        """
2264        Returns a partial list of one attribute for the element block with given ID.
2265
2266        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2267
2268        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY
2269
2270        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
2271        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
2272        :param attrib_index: attribute index (1-based)
2273        :param start: element start index (1-based)
2274        :param count: number of elements
2275        :return: array containing the selected part of the attribute list
2276        """
2277        if start < 1:
2278            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2279        if count < 0:
2280            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2281        num_attrib = self._int_get_num_elem_attrib(internal_id)
2282        if num_attrib > 0:  # faster to check this than if the variable exists like in the function above this one
2283            if attrib_index < 1 or attrib_index > num_attrib:
2284                raise ValueError("Attribute index out of range. Got {}".format(attrib_index))
2285            result = self.data.variables[VAR_ELEM_ATTRIB % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1, attrib_index - 1]
2286        else:
2287            result = []
2288            warnings.warn("Element block {} has no attributes.".format(obj_id))
2289        return result
2290
2291    def get_partial_one_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, attrib_index, start, count):
2292        """
2293        Returns a partial list of one attribute for the specified elements in the element block with given ID.
2294
2295        Array starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
2296        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2297        """
2298        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
2299        return self._int_get_partial_one_elem_attrib(obj_id, internal_id, attrib_index, start, count)

2331    def get_elem_attrib_names(self, obj_id):
2332        """
2333        Returns a list of the names of attributes in the element block with given ID.
2334
2335        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes or attribute names.
2336        """
2337        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
2338        num_attrib = self._int_get_num_elem_attrib(internal_id)
2339        result = []
2340        if num_attrib == 0:
2341            warnings.warn("Element block {} has no attributes.".format(obj_id))
2342        else:
2343            varname = VAR_ELEM_ATTRIB_NAME % internal_id
2344            # Older datasets don't have attribute names
2345            if varname in self.data.variables:
2346                names = self.data.variables[varname][:]
2347                result = util.arrparse(names, len(names), self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2348            else:
2349                warnings.warn("Attributes of element block {} have no names.".format(obj_id))
2350        return result

2358    # Object properties #
2359    #####################
2360
2361    # This method contains a general algorithm for counting the number of properties an object has.
2362    # This is used by the num_*_prop properties which are in turn used by _get_object_property_names
2363    def _get_num_object_properties(self, varname):
2364        """
2365        Returns the number of properties an object has.
2366
2367        :param varname: the netCDF variable name of the property. ("xx_prop_%d") where xx is ns, ss, or eb
2368        :return: number of properties
2369        """
2370        # loop over the prop variables and count how many there are
2371        n = 0
2372        while True:
2373            if varname % (n + 1) in self.data.variables:
2374                n += 1
2375            else:
2376                break
2377        return n
2378
2379    def _get_object_property(self, obj_type: ObjectType, obj_id, name):
2380        """
2381        Returns the value of a specific object's property.
2382
2383        :param obj_type: type of object this id refers to
2384        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
2385        :param name: name of the property
2386        :return: value of the property for the specified object
2387        """
2388        internal_id = self._lookup_id(obj_type, obj_id)
2389        prop = self._get_object_property_array(obj_type, name)
2390        # We don't want to index into prop if it's empty
2391        if len(prop) > 0:
2392            return prop[internal_id - 1]
2393        else:
2394            return None
2395
2396    def get_node_set_property(self, obj_id, name):
2397        """Returns the value of the specified property for the node set with the given ID."""
2398        return self._get_object_property(NODESET, obj_id, name)
2399
2400    def get_side_set_property(self, obj_id, name):
2401        """Returns the value of the specified property for the side set with the given ID."""

2404    def get_elem_block_property(self, obj_id, name):
2405        """Returns the value of the specified property for the element block with the given ID."""

2407
2408    def _get_object_property_array(self, obj_type: ObjectType, name):
2409        """
2410        Returns a list containing all the values of a particular property for objects of a given type.
2411
2412        :param obj_type: type of object this id refers to
2413        :param name: name of the property
2414        :return: array containing values of the property for objects of the given type
2415        """
2416        if obj_type == NODESET:
2417            varname = VAR_NS_PROP
2418        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
2419            varname = VAR_SS_PROP
2420        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
2421            varname = VAR_EB_PROP
2422        else:
2423            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(obj_type))
2424        prop = []
2425        # Search for the property for the right name
2426        # We don't use a for loop over the number of props because that would cost a second loop over the props
2427        n = 1
2428        while True:
2429            if varname % n in self.data.variables:
2430                propname = self.data.variables[varname % n].getncattr(ATTR_NAME)
2431                if propname == name:
2432                    # we've found our property
2433                    prop = self.data.variables[varname % n][:]
2434                    break
2435                else:
2436                    # check next property
2437                    n += 1
2438                    continue
2439            else:
2440                # "xx_prop_n" doesn't exist. name doesn't exist in file
2441                warnings.warn("Property {} does not exist!".format(name))
2442                break
2443        return prop
2444
2445    def get_node_set_property_array(self, name):
2446        """Returns a list containing the values of the specified property for all node sets."""
2447        return self._get_object_property_array(NODESET, name)
2448
2449    def get_side_set_property_array(self, name):
2450        """Returns a list containing the values of the specified property for all side sets."""
2451        return self._get_object_property_array(SIDESET, name)
2452
2453    def get_elem_block_property_array(self, name):
2454        """Returns a list containing the values of the specified property for all element blocks."""
2455        return self._get_object_property_array(ELEMBLOCK, name)
2456
2457    def _get_object_property_names(self, obj_type: ObjectType):
2458        """
2459        Returns a list containing the names of properties defined for objects of a given type.
2460
2461        :param obj_type: type of object
2462        :return: array of property names
2463        """
2464        if obj_type == NODESET:
2465            varname = VAR_NS_PROP
2466            num_props = self.num_node_set_prop
2467        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
2468            varname = VAR_SS_PROP
2469            num_props = self.num_side_set_prop
2470        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
2471            varname = VAR_EB_PROP
2472            num_props = self.num_elem_block_prop
2473        else:
2474            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(obj_type))
2475        # num_props = self._get_num_object_properties(varname)
2476        result = numpy.empty([num_props], self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2477        for n in range(num_props):
2478            result[n] = self.data.variables[varname % (n + 1)].getncattr(ATTR_NAME)
2479        return result
2480
2481    def get_node_set_property_names(self):
2482        """Returns a list of node set property names."""
2483        return self._get_object_property_names(NODESET)
2484
2485    def get_side_set_property_names(self):
2486        """Returns a list of side set property names."""
2487        return self._get_object_property_names(SIDESET)
2488
2489    def get_elem_block_property_names(self):
2490        """Returns a list of element block property names."""
2491        return self._get_object_property_names(ELEMBLOCK)

2497    def get_coords(self):
2498        """Returns a multidimensional array containing the coordinates of all nodes."""
2499        # Technically this incurs an extra call to num_nodes, but the reduced complexity is worth it
2500        return self.get_partial_coords(1, self.num_nodes)
2501
2502    def get_partial_coords(self, start, count):
2503        """
2504        Returns a multidimensional array containing the coordinates of the specified set of nodes.
2505
2506        Array starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
2507        """
2508        if start < 1:
2509            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2510        if count < 0:
2511            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2512        dim_cnt = self.num_dim
2513        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
2514        if num_nodes == 0:
2515            return []
2516        large = self.large_model
2517        if not large:
2518            try:
2519                coord = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD][:, start - 1:start + count - 1]
2520            except KeyError:
2521                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve nodal coordinate array!")
2522        else:
2523            try:
2524                coordx = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_X][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2525            except KeyError:
2526                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve x axis nodal coordinate array!")
2527            if dim_cnt > 1:
2528                try:
2529                    coordy = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_Y][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2530                except KeyError:
2531                    raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve y axis nodal coordinate array!")
2532                if dim_cnt > 2:
2533                    try:
2534                        coordz = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_Z][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2535                    except KeyError:
2536                        raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve z axis nodal coordinate array!")
2537                    coord = numpy.array([coordx, coordy, coordz])
2538                else:
2539                    coord = numpy.array([coordx, coordy])
2540            else:
2541                coord = coordx
2542        return coord
2543
2544    def get_coord_x(self):
2545        """Returns an array containing the x coordinate of all nodes."""
2546        return self.get_partial_coord_x(1, self.num_nodes)
2547
2548    def get_partial_coord_x(self, start, count):
2549        """

2552        Array starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
2553        """
2554        if start < 1:
2555            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2556        if count < 0:
2557            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2558        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
2559        if num_nodes == 0:
2560            return []
2561        large = self.large_model
2562        if not large:
2563            try:
2564                coord = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD][0][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2565            except KeyError:
2566                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve nodal coordinate array!")
2567        else:
2568            try:
2569                coord = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_X][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2570            except KeyError:
2571                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve x axis nodal coordinate array!")
2572        return coord

2636    def get_coord_names(self):
2637        """Returns an array containing the names of the coordinate axes in this database."""
2638        dim_cnt = self.num_dim
2639        try:
2640            names = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_NAMES]
2641        except KeyError:
2642            raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve coordinate name array!")
2643        result = util.arrparse(names, dim_cnt, self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2644        return result

2647    # File records #
2648    ################
2649
2650    def get_info(self):
2651        """Returns an array containing the info records stored in this database."""
2652        num = self.num_info
2653        result = numpy.empty([num], Exodus._MAX_LINE_LENGTH_T)
2654        if num > 0:
2655            try:
2656                infos = self.data.variables[VAR_INFO]
2657            except KeyError:
2658                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve info records from database!")
2659            for i in range(num):
2660                result[i] = util.lineparse(infos[i])
2661        return result
2662
2663    def get_qa(self):
2664        """Returns an n x 4 array containing the QA records stored in this database."""
2665        num = self.num_qa
2666        result = numpy.empty([num, 4], Exodus._MAX_STR_LENGTH_T)
2667        if num > 0:
2668            try:
2669                qas = self.data.variables[VAR_QA]
2670            except KeyError:
2671                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve qa records from database!")
2672            for i in range(num):
2673                for j in range(4):
2674                    result[i, j] = util.lineparse(qas[i, j])
2675        return result

2689    def time_steps(self):
2690        """Returns list of the time steps, 0-indexed"""
2691        return [*range(self.num_time_steps)]
2692
2693    def step_at_time(self, time):
2694        """Given a float time value, return the corresponding time step"""
2695        for index, value in enumerate(self.get_all_times()):
2696            if value == time:
2697                return index
2698        return None

2700    # TODO remove?
2701    def set_nodeset(self, node_set_id, node_ids):
2702        ndx = node_set_id - 1
2703        if "ns_prop1" in self.data.variables:
2704            ndx = numpy.where(self.data.variables["ns_prop1"][:] == node_set_id)[0][0]
2705            ndx += 1
2706
2707        key = "node_ns" + str(ndx)
2708        nodeset = self.data[key]
2709
2710        if "node_num_map" in self.data.variables:
2711            indices = numpy.zeros(len(node_ids))
2712            i = 0
2713            for id in node_ids:
2714                ndx = numpy.where(self.data["node_num_map"][:] == id)[0][0]
2715                indices[i] = ndx
2716                i += 1
2717            nodeset[:] = indices
2718            return
2719        nodeset[:] = node_ids
2720
2721    # TODO remove?
2722    def get_nodes_in_elblock(self, id):
2723        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
2724            return self.ledger.get_connectX(id)
2725
2726        if "node_num_map" in self.data.variables:
2727            raise Exception("Using node num map")
2728        nodeids = self.data["connect" + str(id)]
2729        # flatten it into 1d
2730        nodeids = nodeids[:].flatten()
2731        return nodeids

2739    def diff(self, other):
2740        # # Nodesets
2741        selfNS = self.num_node_sets
2742        otherNS = other.num_node_sets
2743        print("Self # Nodesets:\t{}".format(selfNS))
2744        print("Other # Nodesets:\t{}".format(otherNS))
2745
2746        # # Sidesets
2747        selfSS = self.num_side_sets
2748        otherSS = other.num_side_sets
2749        print("\nSelf # Sidesets:\t{}".format(selfSS))
2750        print("Other # Sidesets:\t{}".format(otherSS))
2751
2752        # # Nodes
2753        selfN = self.num_nodes
2754        otherN = other.num_nodes
2755        print("\nSelf # Nodes:\t\t{}".format(selfN))
2756        print("Other # Nodes:\t\t{}".format(otherN))
2757
2758        # # Elements
2759        selfE = self.num_elem
2760        otherE = other.num_elem
2761        print("\nSelf # Elements:\t{}".format(selfE))
2762        print("Other # Elements:\t{}\n".format(otherE))
2763
2764        # Length of output variables (nodal/elemental)
2765
2766    def diff_nodeset(self, id, other, id2=None):
2767        """
2768        Prints the overlap and difference between two nodesets
2769        :param id: the nodeset ID of the self Exodus object
2770        :param other: the other Exodus object to compare to
2771        :param id2: optional parameter specifying the nodeset ID of other Exodus object. Default to the first id.
2772        """
2773
2774        if other is None:
2775            raise ValueError("Other Exodus file is None")
2776
2777        if id2 is None:
2778            id2 = id
2779        try:
2780            ns1 = self.get_node_set(id)
2781        except KeyError:
2782            raise KeyError("Self Exodus file does not contain nodeset with ID {}".format(id))
2783
2784        try:
2785            ns2 = other.get_node_set(id2)
2786        except KeyError:
2787            raise KeyError("Other Exodus file does not contain nodeset with ID {}".format(id2))
2788
2789        equivalent = numpy.array_equal(numpy.array(sorted(ns1.tolist())), numpy.array(sorted(ns2.tolist())))
2790        if equivalent:
2791            print("Self NS {} contains the same Node IDs as Other NS ID {}".format(id, id2))
2792        else:
2793            print("Self NS ID {} does NOT contain the same nodes as Other NS ID {}".format(id, id2))
2794            intersection = set(ns1) & set(ns2)
2795            print("\tBoth nodesets share the following nodes:\n\t{}".format(sorted(list(intersection))))
2796            ns1_diff = sorted(list(set(ns1) - intersection))
2797            print("\tSelf NS ID {} also contains nodes:\n\t{}".format(id, ns1_diff))
2798            ns2_diff = sorted(list(set(ns2) - intersection))
2799            print("\tOther NS ID {} also contains nodes:\n\t{}\n".format(id2, ns2_diff))

2842    """
2843    Adds new sideset. Takes in element ids, side ids, id of the new sideset, and name of the new sideset. 
2844    Can optionally specify distribution factor and variables. If no distribution factors are specified 
2845    and they are required, placeholder 1s will be inserted. If no variables are specified and they are required, 
2846    placeholder 0s will be inserted. If specifying distribution factors, they must be of size n * len(elem_ids), where
2847    n is a positive integer. If specifying variables, they must be of dimensions 
2848    [number of sideset variables, number of timesteps, number of sides in sideset].

2890    """
2891    Splits an existing side set (specified by ID) into 2 new side sets based on a passed in function. The paramater
2892    'function' should return a boolean and take in a tuple of (element, state). The parameter 'delete' should be True
2893    to delete the original side set after splitting or False to keep the original side set after splitting. An ID for
2894    each of the two new side sets must be passed in, and names for each of the two new side sets can be passed in
2895    but default to the empty string otherwise.
2896    """

2900            raise PermissionError("Need to be in write or append mode to split sideset")
2901        self.ledger.split_sideset(old_ss, function, ss_id1, ss_id2, delete, ss_name1, ss_name2)

2904    Splits an existing side set into 2 new side sets based on a comparison of the x-coordinates of nodes in the sides
2905    and to a user-specified value. Comparison should be one of the following strings:  '<', '>', '<=', '>=', '=', or '!='.
2906    The parameter 'x-value' should be the value that x-coords of the nodes of a side are compared to. The parameter
2907    'all_nodes' should be True if all of the nodes in a given side need to match the criteria of the comparison
2908    or False if only one node needs to meet the criteria of the comparison. The parameter 'delete' should be True to
2909    delete the original side set after splitting or False to keep the original side set after splitting. An ID for
2910    each of the two new side sets must be passed in, and names for each of the two new side sets can be passed in
2911    but default to the empty string otherwise.
2912    """

2915        if self.mode != 'w' and self.mode != 'a':
2916            raise PermissionError("Need to be in write or append mode to split sideset based on x-coord")
2917        self.ledger.split_sideset_x_coords(old_ss, comparison, x_value, all_nodes, ss_id1, ss_id2, delete, ss_name1, ss_name2)

2948        if self.mode != 'w' and self.mode != 'a':
2949            raise PermissionError("Need to be in write or append mode to split sideset based on z-coord")
2950        self.ledger.split_sideset_z_coords(old_ss, comparison, z_value, all_nodes, ss_id1, ss_id2, delete, ss_name1, ss_name2)
2951

2957        :param nodelist: list of node IDs that make up the new element
2958        """
2959        if self.mode != 'w' and self.mode != 'a':
2960            raise PermissionError("Need to be in write or append mode to add element")

2990        Adds a single corresponding sideset of the external faces

3001    def write(self, path=None):
3002        if self.mode != 'w' and self.mode != 'a':
3003            raise PermissionError("Need to be in write or append mode to write")
3004        elif self.mode == 'a' and path is None:
3005            raise AttributeError("Must specify a new path when in append mode")
3006        elif self.mode == 'w' and path is not None:
3007            raise AttributeError("Do not specify a new path in write mode. Initialization path will be used")
3008        self.ledger.write(path)

  32class Exodus:
  33    """
  34    The Exodus class represents an opened Exodus II file.
  35
  36    The first step in doing anything to an Exodus II file is to create a new Exodus object from it (See
  37    `Exodus.__init__` for how to do this).
  38
  39    You can read and modify an Exodus II file using ``Exodus``'s properties and functions. You may not modify
  40    properties, but you can get them with minimal performance impact. Calling any functions will read data from the file
  41    on disk, and this data is not cached by the library, so you should avoid multiple identical function calls whenever
  42    possible.
  43
  44    Many of the functions of ``Exodus`` require "1-based" indices. To clarify: Exodus data is usually accessed starting
  45    from 1 rather than 0 as is more common in computer programming. If a function requests 1-based indices that means
  46    list indexing starts at 1. If a function requests 0-based indices that means list indexing starts at 0.
  47
  48    Once you are finished with the Exodus II file, call `Exodus.close` to safely close the file.
  49    """
  50    _FORMAT_MAP = {'EX_NETCDF4': 'NETCDF4',
  51                   'EX_LARGE_MODEL': 'NETCDF3_64BIT_OFFSET',
  52                   'EX_NORMAL_MODEL': 'NETCDF3_CLASSIC',
  53                   'EX_64BIT_DATA': 'NETCDF3_64BIT_DATA'}
  54    # Default values
  55    _MAX_STR_LENGTH = 32
  56    _MAX_STR_LENGTH_T = 'U32'
  57    _MAX_NAME_LENGTH = 32
  58    _MAX_LINE_LENGTH = 80
  59    _MAX_LINE_LENGTH_T = 'U80'
  60    _EXODUS_VERSION = 7.22
  61
  62    # Should creating a new file (mode 'w') be a function on its own?
  63    def __init__(self, path, mode, shared=False, format='EX_NETCDF4', word_size=4):
  64        """
  65        Exodus constructor.
  66
  67        :param path: path to the Exodus II file to open as a string.
  68        :param mode: access mode. 'r' opens the file in read only mode. 'a' is append mode; it allows you to modify the
  69        file as well as read from it. 'w' is write mode; it creates a new file at the specified path and opens it as in
  70        append mode.
  71        :param shared: if `True` the file will open with unbuffered shared access for NetCDF 3 classic, 64bit offset,
  72        and 64bit data models (EX_NORMAL_MODEL, EX_LARGE_MODEL, EX_64BIT_DATA).
  73        :param format: if `mode` is 'w' then this is the underlying netCDF format the database will use.
  74        :param word_size: if `mode` is 'w' then this is the floating point word size used in the database.
  75        """
  76        # clobber and format and word_size only apply to mode w
  77        if mode not in ['r', 'w', 'a']:
  78            raise ValueError("mode must be 'w', 'r', or 'a', got '{}'".format(mode))
  79        if format not in Exodus._FORMAT_MAP.keys():
  80            raise ValueError("invalid file format: '{}'".format(format))
  81        if word_size not in [4, 8]:
  82            raise ValueError("word_size must be 4 or 8 bytes, {} is not supported".format(word_size))
  83        nc_format = Exodus._FORMAT_MAP[format]
  84
  85        self.mode = mode
  86        self.path = path
  87
  88        # file should never actually be opened in append mode
  89        # if append mode is specified, open file in read mode and write out changes to separate file
  90        if mode == 'a':
  91            mode = 'r'
  92
  93        # Sets shared mode if the user asked for it. I have no idea what this does :)
  94        if shared:
  95            smode = mode + 's'
  96        else:
  97            smode = mode
  98        try:
  99            self.data = nc.Dataset(path, smode, clobber=False, format=nc_format)
 100        except FileNotFoundError:
 101            raise FileNotFoundError("file '{}' does not exist".format(path)) from None
 102        except PermissionError:
 103            raise PermissionError("You do not have access to '{}'".format(path)) from None
 104        # this can actually hide some errors which is bad.
 105        # except OSError:
 106        #     raise OSError("file '{}' already exists".format(path)) from None
 107
 108        if self.mode == 'w':
 109            # This is important according to ex_open.c
 110            self.data.set_fill_off()
 111
 112        if self.mode == 'a' or self.mode == 'w':
 113            self.ledger = Ledger(self)
 114
 115        # save path variable for future use
 116        self.path = path
 117
 118        # We will read a bunch of data here to make sure it exists and warn the user if they might want to fix their
 119        # file. We don't save anything to memory so that if our data updates we don't have to update it in memory too.
 120        # This is the same practice used in the C library so its probably a good idea.
 121
 122        # Initialize all the important parameters
 123        if mode == 'w':
 124            self.data.setncattr('title', 'Untitled database')
 125            self.data.createDimension('len_string', Exodus._MAX_STR_LENGTH + 1)
 126            self.data.createDimension('len_name', Exodus._MAX_NAME_LENGTH + 1)
 127            self.data.createDimension('len_line', Exodus._MAX_LINE_LENGTH + 1)
 128            self.data.setncattr('maximum_name_length', Exodus._MAX_NAME_LENGTH)
 129            self.data.setncattr('version', Exodus._EXODUS_VERSION)
 130            self.data.setncattr('api_version', Exodus._EXODUS_VERSION)
 131            self.data.setncattr('floating_point_word_size', word_size)
 132            file_size = 0
 133            if nc_format == 'NETCDF3_64BIT_OFFSET':
 134                file_size = 1
 135            self.data.setncattr('file_size', file_size)
 136            int64bit_status = 0
 137            if nc_format == 'NETCDF3_64BIT_DATA':
 138                int64bit_status = 1
 139            self.data.setncattr('int64_status', int64bit_status)
 140
 141        # Check version compatibility
 142        ver = self.version
 143        if ver < 2.0:
 144            raise RuntimeError(
 145                "Unsupported file version {:.2f}! Only versions >2.0 are supported.".format(ver))
 146
 147        # Read word size stored in file
 148        ws = self.word_size
 149        if ws == 4:
 150            self._float = numpy.float32
 151        elif ws == 8:
 152            self._float = numpy.float64
 153        else:
 154            raise ValueError("file contains a word size of {} which is not supported".format(ws))
 155
 156        if self.int64_status == 0:
 157            self._int = numpy.int32
 158        else:
 159            self._int = numpy.int64
 160
 161        # important for storing names in numpy arrays
 162        self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T = 'U%s' % self.max_allowed_name_length
 163
 164    def to_float(self, n):
 165        """Returns ``n`` converted to the floating-point type stored in the database."""
 166        # Convert a number to the floating point type the database is using
 167        return self._float(n)
 168
 169    def to_int(self, n):
 170        """Returns ``n`` converted to the integer type stored in the database."""
 171        # Convert a number to the integer type the database is using
 172        return self._int(n)
 173
 174    @property
 175    def float(self):
 176        """The floating-point type stored in the database."""
 177        # Returns floating point type of floating point numbers stored in the database
 178        # You may use whatever crazy types you want while coding, but convert them before storing them in the DB
 179        return self._float
 180
 181    @property
 182    def int(self):
 183        """The integer type stored in the database."""
 184        # Returns integer type of integers stored in the database
 185        return self._int
 186

 204        """The database title."""

 208            AttributeError("Database title could not be found")

 210    @property
 211    def max_allowed_name_length(self):
 212        """The maximum allowed length for variable/dimension/attribute names in this database."""
 213        max_name_len = Exodus._MAX_NAME_LENGTH
 214        if DIM_NAME_LENGTH in self.data.dimensions:
 215            # Subtract 1 because in C an extra null character is added for C reasons
 216            max_name_len = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NAME_LENGTH].size - 1
 217        return max_name_len
 218
 219    @property
 220    def max_used_name_length(self):
 221        """The maximum used length for variable/dimension/attribute names in this database."""
 222        # 32 is the default size consistent with other databases
 223        max_used_name_len = 32
 224        if ATT_MAX_NAME_LENGTH in self.data.ncattrs():
 225            # The length does not include the added null character from C
 226            max_used_name_len = self.data.getncattr(ATT_MAX_NAME_LENGTH)
 227        return max_used_name_len
 228

 231        """Maximum QA record string length."""
 232        # See ex_put_qa.c @ line 119. This record is created and used when adding QA records
 233        max_str_len = Exodus._MAX_STR_LENGTH
 234        if DIM_STRING_LENGTH in self.data.dimensions:
 235            # Subtract 1 because in C an extra character is added for C reasons
 236            max_str_len = self.data.dimensions[DIM_STRING_LENGTH].size - 1
 237        return max_str_len

 244        if DIM_LINE_LENGTH in self.data.dimensions:

 270    @property
 271    def large_model(self):
 272        """
 273        Describes how coordinates are stored in this database.
 274
 275        If true: nodal coordinates and variables are stored in separate x, y, z variables.
 276        If false: nodal coordinates and variables are stored in a single variable.
 277
 278        :return: 1 if stored separately (large), 0 if stored in a blob
 279        """
 280        # According to a comment in ex_utils.c @ line 1614
 281        # "Basically, the difference is whether the coordinates and nodal variables are stored in a blob (xyz components
 282        # together) or as a variable per component per nodal_variable."
 283        # This is important for coordinate getter functions
 284        if ATT_FILE_SIZE in self.data.ncattrs():
 285            return self.data.getncattr(ATT_FILE_SIZE)
 286        else:
 287            return 0
 288            # No warning is raised because older files just don't have this
 289
 290    @property
 291    def int64_status(self):
 292        """
 293        64-bit integer support for this database.
 294
 295        Use ``int()`` to get the integer type used by this database.
 296
 297        :return: 1 if 64-bit integers are supported, 0 otherwise
 298        """
 299        # Determines whether the file uses int64s
 300        if ATT_64BIT_INT in self.data.ncattrs():
 301            return self.data.getncattr(ATT_64BIT_INT)
 302        else:
 303            return 1 if self.data.data_model == 'NETCDF3_64BIT_DATA' else 0
 304            # No warning is raised because older files just don't have this
 305

 480    ##############
 481    # Order maps #
 482    ##############
 483
 484    def get_elem_order_map(self):
 485        """Returns the optional element order map for this database."""
 486        num_elem = self.num_elem
 487        if num_elem == 0:
 488            warnings.warn("Cannot retrieve an element order map if there are no elements!")
 489            return
 490        if VAR_ELEM_ORDER_MAP not in self.data.variables:
 491            # Return a default array from 1 to the number of elements
 492            warnings.warn("There is no element order map in this database!")
 493            return numpy.arange(1, num_elem + 1, dtype=self.int)
 494        return self.data.variables[VAR_ELEM_ORDER_MAP][:]
 495
 496    # OK so we have two types of maps on the database: ID maps & ORDER maps (also called NUMBER maps).
 497    # ID maps used to be called number maps and number maps used to be called order maps, which is super confusing.
 498    # This library supports the classic element order map (as defined in Exodus II API documentation), but does not
 499    # support the new 'number maps' that the SEACAS C library has support for.
 500
 501    ###########
 502    # ID maps #
 503    ###########
 504
 505    # Below is an explanation of entity IDs in lieu of a proper one in any official documentation.
 506    # Nodes and elements have two IDs: an internal ID used by Exodus and all Exodus libraries, and a user-defined ID
 507    # used by analysts interacting with the database. To translate user-defined IDs to internal IDs, Exodus files store
 508    # an optional node ID map and element ID map. If they are not defined, user-defined IDs = internal IDs. This map
 509    # stores the user-defined ID for an entity at the index internal ID-1. We subtract 1 from the internal ID because
 510    # internal IDs are 1-based, meaning they start counting up from 1, not 0!
 511    # When working with element connectivity lists, we have to manually calculate the internal ID of each element since
 512    # connectivity lists do not store element IDs, only their constituent nodes.
 513    # The general formula to get the internal ID of the element at index i of element block n is as follows:
 514    # offset = sum(num_elem_in_block(1), num_elem_in_block(2), ..., num_elem_in_block(n - 1);
 515    # internal_id = offset + i + 1;
 516    # Example: EB1 has 7 elements, EB2 has 10 elements. The internal ID of the 4th element in EB2 is 7 + 3 + 1
 517
 518    def get_node_id_map(self):
 519        """Return the node ID map for this database."""
 520        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
 521        return self.get_partial_node_id_map(1, num_nodes)
 522
 523    def get_reverse_node_id_dict(self):
 524        """Returns a dictionary with user-defined IDs as the keys and internal IDs as the values."""
 525        nim = self.get_node_id_map()
 526        u2i_map = {}
 527        for i in range(self.num_nodes):
 528            u2i_map[nim[i]] = i + 1
 529        return u2i_map
 530
 531    def get_partial_node_id_map(self, start, count):
 532        """
 533        Return a subset of the node ID map for this database.
 534
 535        Subset starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
 536        """
 537        # Start is 1 based (>0).  start + count - 1 <= number of nodes
 538        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
 539        if num_nodes == 0:
 540            raise KeyError("Cannot retrieve a node id map if there are no nodes!")
 541        if start < 1:
 542            raise ValueError("start index must be greater than 0")
 543        if start + count - 1 > num_nodes:
 544            raise ValueError("start index + node count is larger than the total number of nodes")
 545        if VAR_NODE_ID_MAP not in self.data.variables:
 546            # Return a default array from start to start + count exclusive
 547            warnings.warn("There is no node id map in this database!")
 548            return numpy.arange(start, start + count, dtype=self.int)
 549        return self.data.variables[VAR_NODE_ID_MAP][start - 1:start + count - 1]
 550
 551    def get_elem_id_map(self):
 552        """Return the element ID map for this database."""
 553        num_elem = self.num_elem
 554        return self.get_partial_elem_id_map(1, num_elem)
 555
 556    def get_reverse_elem_id_dict(self):
 557        """Returns a dictionary with user-defined IDs as the keys and internal IDs as the values."""
 558        eim = self.get_elem_id_map()
 559        u2i_map = {}
 560        for i in range(self.num_elem):
 561            u2i_map[eim[i]] = i + 1
 562        return u2i_map
 563
 564    def get_partial_elem_id_map(self, start, count):
 565        """
 566        Return a subset of the element ID map for this database.
 567
 568        Subset starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
 569        """
 570        # Start is 1 based (>0).  start + count - 1 <= number of nodes
 571        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
 572            return self.ledger.get_elem_num_map()[start - 1:start + count - 1]
 573
 574        num_elem = self.num_elem
 575        if num_elem == 0:
 576            raise KeyError("Cannot retrieve a element id map if there are no elements!")
 577        if start < 1:
 578            raise ValueError("start index must be greater than 0")
 579        if start + count - 1 > num_elem:
 580            raise ValueError("start index + element count is larger than the total number of elements")
 581        if VAR_ELEM_ID_MAP not in self.data.variables:
 582            # Return a default array from start to start + count exclusive
 583            warnings.warn("There is no element id map in this database!")
 584            return numpy.arange(start, start + count, dtype=self.int)
 585        return self.data.variables[VAR_ELEM_ID_MAP][start - 1:start + count - 1]
 586
 587    def get_elem_id_map_for_block(self, obj_id):
 588        """Reads the element ID map for the element block with specified ID."""
 589        if self.num_elem_blk == 0:
 590            raise KeyError("There are no element blocks in this database!")
 591        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
 592        num_elem, _, _, _ = self._int_get_elem_block_params(obj_id, internal_id)
 593        offset = 0
 594        emap = self.get_elem_id_map()
 595        for i in range(1, internal_id):
 596            n, _, _, _ = self._int_get_elem_block_params(emap[i - 1], i)
 597            offset += n
 598        return self.get_partial_elem_id_map(offset + 1, num_elem)
 599
 600    def get_node_set_id_map(self):
 601        """Returns the id map for node sets (ns_prop1)."""
 602        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
 603            return self.ledger.get_node_set_id_map()
 604
 605        try:
 606            table = self.data.variables[VAR_NS_ID_MAP][:]
 607        except KeyError:
 608            raise KeyError("Node set id map is missing from this database!".format(type))
 609        return table
 610
 611    def get_side_set_id_map(self):
 612        """Returns the id map for side sets (ss_prop1)."""
 613        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
 614            self.ledger.get_side_set_id_map()
 615        try:
 616            table = self.data.variables[VAR_SS_ID_MAP][:]
 617        except KeyError:
 618            raise KeyError("Side set id map is missing from this database!".format(type))
 619        return table
 620
 621    def get_elem_block_id_map(self):
 622        """Returns the id map for element blocks (eb_prop1)."""
 623        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
 624            return self.ledger.get_eb_prop1()[:]
 625
 626        try:
 627            table = self.data.variables[VAR_EB_ID_MAP][:]
 628        except KeyError:
 629            raise KeyError("Element block id map is missing from this database!".format(type))
 630        return table
 631
 632    def _lookup_id(self, obj_type: ObjectType, num):
 633        """
 634        Returns the internal ID of a set or block of the given type and user-defined ID.
 635
 636        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
 637
 638        :param obj_type: type of object this id refers to
 639        :param num: user-defined ID (aka number) of the set/block
 640        :return: internal ID
 641        """
 642        if obj_type == NODESET:
 643            table = self.get_node_set_id_map()
 644        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
 645            if (self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a'):
 646                table = self.ledger.get_side_set_id_map()
 647            else:
 648                table = self.get_side_set_id_map()
 649        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
 650            table = self.get_elem_block_id_map()
 651        else:
 652            raise ValueError("{} is not a valid set/block type!".format(obj_type))
 653        # The C library caches information about sets including whether its sequential, so it can skip a lot of this
 654        internal_id = 1
 655        for table_id in table:
 656            if table_id == num:
 657                break
 658            internal_id += 1
 659        if internal_id > len(table):
 660            raise KeyError("Could not find set/block of type {} with id {}".format(obj_type, num))
 661        return internal_id
 662        # The C library also does some crazy stuff with what might be the ns_status array
 663
 664    def get_node_set_number(self, obj_id):
 665        """
 666        Returns the internal ID (1-based) of the node set with the user-defined ID.
 667
 668        Note that this function is O(n) complexity for n number of node sets. While useful for quick tests, you should
 669        create an ID lookup table yourself if you plan to convert IDs often.
 670        """
 671        return self._lookup_id(NODESET, obj_id)
 672
 673    def get_side_set_number(self, obj_id):
 674        """
 675        Returns the internal ID (1-based) of the side set with the user-defined ID.
 676
 677        Note that this function is O(n) complexity for n number of node sets. While useful for quick tests, you should
 678        create an ID lookup table yourself if you plan to convert IDs often.
 679        """
 680        return self._lookup_id(SIDESET, obj_id)
 681
 682    def get_elem_block_number(self, obj_id):
 683        """
 684        Returns the internal ID (1-based) of the elem block with the user-defined ID.
 685
 686        Note that this function is O(n) complexity for n number of node sets. While useful for quick tests, you should
 687        create an ID lookup table yourself if you plan to convert IDs often.
 688        """
 689        return self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)

 695    def get_all_times(self):
 696        """Returns an array of all time values from all time steps from this database."""
 697        try:
 698            result = self.data.variables[VAR_TIME_WHOLE][:]
 699        except KeyError:
 700            raise KeyError("Could not retrieve time steps from database!")
 701        return result
 702
 703    def get_time(self, time_step):
 704        """
 705        Returns the time value for specified time step.
 706
 707        Time steps are 1-indexed. The first time step is at 1, and the last at num_time_steps.
 708        """
 709        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
 710        if num_steps <= 0:
 711            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
 712        if time_step <= 0 or time_step > num_steps:
 713            raise ValueError("Time step out of range. Got {}".format(time_step))
 714        return self.get_all_times()[time_step - 1]
 715
 716    def get_nodal_var_at_time(self, time_step, var_index):
 717        """
 718        Returns the values of the nodal variable with given index at specified time step.
 719
 720        Time step and variable index are both 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 721        """
 722        return self.get_nodal_var_across_times(time_step, time_step, var_index)[0]
 723
 724    def get_nodal_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
 725        """
 726        Returns the values of the nodal variable with given index between specified time steps (inclusive).
 727
 728        Time steps and variable index are both 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 729        """
 730        return self.get_partial_nodal_var_across_times(start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index, 1, self.num_nodes)
 731
 732    def get_partial_nodal_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index, start_index, count):
 733        """
 734        Returns partial values of a nodal variable between specified time steps (inclusive).
 735
 736        Time steps, variable index, ID and start index are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 737        Array starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
 738        """
 739        if self.num_nodes == 0:
 740            return [[]]
 741        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
 742        if num_steps <= 0:
 743            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
 744        if start_time_step <= 0 or start_time_step > num_steps:
 745            raise ValueError("Start time step out of range. Got {}".format(start_time_step))
 746        if end_time_step <= 0 or end_time_step < start_time_step or end_time_step > num_steps:
 747            raise ValueError("End time step out of range. Got {}".format(end_time_step))
 748        if var_index <= 0 or var_index > self.num_node_var:
 749            raise ValueError("Variable index out of range. Got {}".format(var_index))
 750        if start_index <= 0:
 751            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
 752        if count < 0:
 753            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
 754        if not self.large_model:
 755            # All vars stored in one variable
 756            try:
 757                # Do not subtract 1 from end (inclusive)
 758                result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_NOD_VAR_SMALL][
 759                         start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, var_index - 1, start_index - 1:start_index + count - 1]
 760            except KeyError:
 761                raise KeyError("Could not find the nodal variables in this database!")
 762        else:
 763            # Each var to its own variable
 764            try:
 765                result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_NOD_VAR_LARGE % var_index][start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, :]
 766            except KeyError:
 767                raise KeyError("Could not find nodal variable {} in this database!".format(var_index))
 768        return result
 769
 770    def get_global_vars_at_time(self, time_step):
 771        """
 772        Returns the values of the all global variables at specified time step.
 773
 774        Time steps are 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 775        """
 776        return self.get_global_vars_across_times(time_step, time_step)[0]
 777
 778    def get_global_vars_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step):
 779        """
 780        Returns the values of the all global variables between specified time steps (inclusive).
 781
 782        Time steps are 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 783        """
 784        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
 785        if num_steps <= 0:
 786            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
 787        if start_time_step <= 0 or start_time_step > num_steps:
 788            raise ValueError("Time step out of range. Got {}".format(start_time_step))
 789        if end_time_step <= 0 or end_time_step < start_time_step or end_time_step > num_steps:
 790            raise ValueError("End time step out of range. Got {}".format(end_time_step))
 791        try:
 792            # Do not subtract 1 from end (inclusive)
 793            result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_GLO_VAR][start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, :]
 794        except KeyError:
 795            raise KeyError("Could not find global variables in this database!")
 796        return result

 806    def get_global_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
 807        """
 808        Returns the values of the global variable with given index between specified time steps (inclusive).
 809
 810        Time steps and variable index are both 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 811        """
 812        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
 813        if num_steps <= 0:
 814            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
 815        if start_time_step <= 0 or start_time_step > num_steps:
 816            raise ValueError("Time step out of range. Got {}".format(start_time_step))
 817        if end_time_step <= 0 or end_time_step < start_time_step or end_time_step > num_steps:
 818            raise ValueError("End time step out of range. Got {}".format(end_time_step))
 819        if var_index <= 0 or var_index > self.num_global_var:
 820            raise ValueError("Variable index out of range. Got {}".format(var_index))
 821        try:
 822            result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_GLO_VAR][start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, var_index - 1]
 823        except KeyError:
 824            raise KeyError("Could not find global variables in this database!")
 825        return result
 826
 827    def _int_get_partial_object_var_across_times(self, obj_type: ObjectType, internal_id, start_time_step,
 828                                                 end_time_step, var_index,
 829                                                 start_index, count):
 830        """
 831        Returns partial values of an element block variable between specified time steps (inclusive).
 832
 833        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
 834
 835        :param obj_type: type of object this id refers to
 836        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
 837        :param start_time_step: start time (inclusive)
 838        :param end_time_step:  end time (inclusive)
 839        :param var_index: variable index (1-based)
 840        :param start_index: element start index (1-based)
 841        :param count: number of elements
 842        :return: 2d array storing the partial variable array at each time step
 843        """
 844
 845        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
 846        if num_steps <= 0:
 847            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
 848        if start_time_step <= 0 or start_time_step > num_steps:
 849            raise ValueError("Time step out of range. Got {}".format(start_time_step))
 850        if end_time_step <= 0 or end_time_step < start_time_step or end_time_step > num_steps:
 851            raise ValueError("End time step out of range. Got {}".format(end_time_step))
 852
 853        if obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
 854            varname = VAR_VALS_ELEM_VAR
 855            numvar = self.num_elem_block_var
 856        elif obj_type == NODESET:
 857            varname = VAR_VALS_NS_VAR
 858            numvar = self.num_node_set_var
 859        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
 860            varname = VAR_VALS_SS_VAR
 861            numvar = self.num_side_set_var
 862        else:
 863            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(obj_type))
 864
 865        if var_index <= 0 or var_index > numvar:
 866            raise ValueError("Variable index out of range. Got {}".format(var_index))
 867        if start_index <= 0:
 868            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
 869        if count < 0:
 870            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
 871        try:
 872            result = self.data.variables[varname % (var_index, internal_id)][
 873                     start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, start_index - 1:start_index + count - 1]
 874        except KeyError:
 875            raise KeyError("Could not find variables of type {} in this database!".format(obj_type))
 876        return result
 877
 878    def get_elem_block_var_at_time(self, obj_id, time_step, var_index):
 879        """
 880        Returns the values of variable with index stored in the element block with id at time step.
 881
 882        Time step, variable index, and ID are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 883        """
 884        return self.get_elem_block_var_across_times(obj_id, time_step, time_step, var_index)[0]
 885
 886    def get_elem_block_var_across_times(self, obj_id, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
 887        """
 888        Returns the values of variable with index stored in the element block with id between time steps (inclusive).
 889
 890        Time steps, variable index, and ID are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 891        """
 892        # This method cannot simply call its partial version because we cannot know the number of elements to read
 893        #  without looking up the id first. This extra id lookup call is slow, so we get around it with a helper method.
 894        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
 895        size = self._int_get_elem_block_params(obj_id, internal_id)[0]
 896        return self._int_get_partial_object_var_across_times(ELEMBLOCK, internal_id, start_time_step, end_time_step,
 897                                                             var_index, 1, size)
 898
 899    def get_partial_elem_block_var_across_times(self, obj_id, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index, start_index,
 900                                                count):
 901        """
 902        Returns partial values of an element block variable between specified time steps (inclusive).
 903
 904        Time steps, variable index, ID and start index are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
 905        Array starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
 906        """
 907        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
 908        return self._int_get_partial_object_var_across_times(ELEMBLOCK, internal_id, start_time_step, end_time_step,
 909                                                             var_index, start_index, count)

 973    def _get_truth_table(self, obj_type: ObjectType):
 974        """
 975        Returns the truth table for variables of a given object type.
 976
 977        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
 978
 979        :param obj_type: type of object
 980        :return: truth table
 981        """
 982        if obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
 983            tabname = VAR_ELEM_TAB
 984            valname = VAR_VALS_ELEM_VAR
 985            num_entity = self.num_elem_blk
 986            num_var = self.num_elem_block_var
 987        elif obj_type == NODESET:
 988            tabname = VAR_NS_TAB
 989            valname = VAR_VALS_NS_VAR
 990            num_entity = self.num_node_sets
 991            num_var = self.num_node_set_var
 992        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
 993            tabname = VAR_SS_TAB
 994            valname = VAR_VALS_SS_VAR
 995            num_entity = self.num_side_sets
 996            num_var = self.num_side_set_var
 997        else:
 998            raise ValueError("Invalid object type {}!".format(obj_type))
 999        if tabname in self.data.variables:
1000            result = self.data.variables[tabname][:]
1001        else:
1002            # we have to figure it out for ourselves
1003            result = numpy.zeros((num_entity, num_var), dtype=self.int)
1004            for e in range(num_entity):
1005                for v in range(num_var):
1006                    if valname % (v + 1, e + 1) in self.data.variables:
1007                        result[e, v] = 1
1008        return result
1009
1010    def get_elem_block_truth_table(self):
1011        """Returns the variable truth table for element blocks."""
1012        return self._get_truth_table(ELEMBLOCK)
1013
1014    def get_node_set_truth_table(self):
1015        """Returns the variable truth table for node sets."""
1016        return self._get_truth_table(NODESET)
1017
1018    def get_side_set_truth_table(self):
1019        """Returns the variable truth table for side sets."""
1020        return self._get_truth_table(SIDESET)
1021
1022    def _get_var_names(self, var_type: VariableType):
1023        """
1024        Returns a list of variable names for objects of a given type.
1025
1026        :param var_type: the type of variable
1027        :return: a list of variable names
1028        """
1029        if var_type == GLOBAL_VAR:
1030            varname = VAR_NAME_GLO_VAR
1031        elif var_type == NODAL_VAR:
1032            varname = VAR_NAME_NOD_VAR
1033        elif var_type == ELEMENTAL_VAR:
1034            varname = VAR_NAME_ELEM_VAR
1035        elif var_type == NODESET_VAR:
1036            varname = VAR_NAME_NS_VAR
1037        elif var_type == SIDESET_VAR:
1038            varname = VAR_NAME_SS_VAR
1039        else:
1040            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(var_type))
1041        try:
1042            names = self.data.variables[varname][:]
1043        except KeyError:
1044            raise KeyError("No {} variable names stored in database!".format(var_type))
1045        result = numpy.empty([len(names)], self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
1046        for i in range(len(names)):
1047            result[i] = util.lineparse(names[i])
1048        return result
1049
1050    def has_var_names(self, var_type: VariableType):
1051        """
1052        Test if this Exodus file has variable names for a variable type.
1053
1054        :param var_type: GLOBAL_VAR, NODAL_VAR, ELEMENTAL_VAR, NODESET_VAR, or SIDESET_VAR from `exodusutils.constants`
1055        :return: True if this variable type has names defined, false otherwise
1056        """
1057        if var_type == GLOBAL_VAR:
1058            varname = VAR_NAME_GLO_VAR
1059        elif var_type == NODAL_VAR:
1060            varname = VAR_NAME_NOD_VAR
1061        elif var_type == ELEMENTAL_VAR:
1062            varname = VAR_NAME_ELEM_VAR
1063        elif var_type == NODESET_VAR:
1064            varname = VAR_NAME_NS_VAR
1065        elif var_type == SIDESET_VAR:
1066            varname = VAR_NAME_SS_VAR
1067        else:
1068            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(var_type))
1069        return varname in self.data.variables
1070

1091    def _get_var_name(self, var_type, index):
1092        """Returns variable name of variable with given index of given object type."""
1093        names = self._get_var_names(var_type)
1094        try:
1095            name = names[index - 1]
1096        except IndexError:
1097            raise IndexError("Variable index out of range. Got {}".format(index))
1098        return name

1124    def _int_get_partial_node_set(self, obj_id, internal_id, start, count):
1125        """
1126        Returns a partial array of the nodes contained in the node set with given ID.
1127
1128        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
1129
1130        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
1131        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
1132        :param start: node start index (1-based)
1133        :param count: number of nodes
1134        :return: array containing the selected part of the node set
1135        """
1136        num_sets = self.num_node_sets
1137        if num_sets == 0:
1138            raise KeyError("No node sets are stored in this database!")
1139        if start < 1:
1140            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
1141        if count < 0:
1142            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
1143        try:
1144            set = self.data.variables[VAR_NODE_NS % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1]
1145        except KeyError:
1146            raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve node set with id {} ('{}')".format(obj_id, VAR_NODE_NS % internal_id))
1147        return set
1148
1149    def _int_get_partial_node_set_df(self, obj_id, internal_id, start, count):
1150        """
1151        Returns a partial array of the distribution factors contained in the node set with given ID.
1152
1153        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
1154
1155        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
1156        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
1157        :param start: node start index (1-based)
1158        :param count: number of nodes
1159        :return: array containing the selected part of the node set distribution factors list
1160        """
1161        num_sets = self.num_node_sets
1162        if num_sets == 0:
1163            raise KeyError("No node sets are stored in this database!")
1164        if start < 1:
1165            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
1166        if count < 0:
1167            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
1168        if ('dist_fact_ns%d' % internal_id) in self.data.variables:
1169            set = self.data.variables[VAR_DF_NS % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1]
1170        else:
1171            warnings.warn("This database does not contain dist factors for node set {}".format(obj_id))
1172            set = []
1173        return set
1174
1175    def _int_get_node_set_params(self, obj_id, internal_id):
1176        """
1177        Returns a tuple containing the parameters for the node set with given ID.
1178
1179        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
1180
1181        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
1182        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
1183        :return: (number of nodes, number of distribution factors)
1184        """
1185        num_sets = self.num_node_sets
1186        if num_sets == 0:
1187            raise KeyError("No node sets are stored in this database!")
1188        try:
1189            num_entries = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_NODE_NS % internal_id].size
1190        except KeyError:
1191            raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve number of entries in node set with id {} ('{}')"
1192                           .format(obj_id, DIM_NUM_NODE_NS % internal_id))
1193        if (VAR_DF_NS % internal_id) in self.data.variables:
1194            num_df = num_entries
1195        else:
1196            num_df = 0
1197        return num_entries, num_df
1198
1199    def get_node_set(self, identifier):
1200        """Returns an array of the nodes contained in the node set with given ID."""
1201        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1202            return self.ledger.get_node_set(identifier)
1203
1204        internal_id = self._lookup_id(NODESET, identifier)
1205        size = self._int_get_node_set_params(identifier, internal_id)[0]
1206        return self._int_get_partial_node_set(identifier, internal_id, 1, size)
1207

1209        """
1210        Returns a partial array of the nodes contained in the node set with given ID.
1211
1212        Array starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
1213        """
1214        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1215            return self.ledger.get_partial_node_set(identifier, start, count)
1216
1217        internal_id = self._lookup_id(NODESET, identifier)
1218        return self._int_get_partial_node_set(identifier, internal_id, start, count)

1244    def _int_get_partial_side_set(self, obj_id, internal_id, start, count):
1245        """
1246        Returns tuple containing a subset of the elements and side contained in the side set with given ID.
1247
1248        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
1249
1250        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
1251        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
1252        :param start: element start index (1-based)
1253        :param count: number of elements
1254        :return: tuple containing the selected part of the side set of format: (elements, corresponding sides)
1255        """
1256        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1257            return self.ledger._int_get_partial_side_set(obj_id, internal_id, start, count)
1258        
1259        num_sets = self.num_side_sets
1260        if num_sets == 0:
1261            raise KeyError("No side sets are stored in this database!")
1262        if start < 1:
1263            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
1264        if count < 0:
1265            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
1266        try:
1267            elmset = self.data.variables[VAR_ELEM_SS % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1]
1268        except KeyError:
1269            raise KeyError(
1270                "Failed to retrieve elements of side set with id {} ('{}')".format(obj_id, VAR_ELEM_SS % internal_id))
1271        try:
1272            sset = self.data.variables[VAR_SIDE_SS % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1]
1273        except KeyError:
1274            raise KeyError(
1275                "Failed to retrieve sides of side set with id {} ('{}')".format(obj_id, VAR_SIDE_SS % internal_id))
1276        return elmset, sset
1277
