1344    def get_side_set_node_count_list(self, obj_id):
1345        """Returns array of number of nodes per side/face."""
1346        # Adapted from ex_get_side_set_node_count.c
1347        internal_id = self._lookup_id(SIDESET, obj_id)
1348        num_eb = self.num_elem_blk
1349        ndim = self.num_dim
1350        num_ss_elem, _ = self._int_get_side_set_params(obj_id, internal_id)
1351        elem_list, side_list = self.get_side_set(obj_id)
1352        ss_elem_idx = numpy.argsort(elem_list)
1353        eb_id_map = self.get_elem_block_id_map()
1354        eb_params = []
1355        elem_ctr = 0
1356        for i in range(num_eb):
1357            id = eb_id_map[i]
1358            eb_params.append(self._int_get_elem_block_param_object(id, ndim))
1359            elem_ctr += eb_params[i].num_elem_in_blk
1360            eb_params[i].elem_ctr = elem_ctr
1361        node_count_list = numpy.empty(num_ss_elem, self.int)
1362        j = 0  # current elem block
1363        for ii in range(num_ss_elem):
1364            i = ss_elem_idx[ii]
1365            elem = elem_list[i]
1366            side = side_list[i] - 1  # 0 based side
1367            while j < num_eb:
1368                if elem <= eb_params[j].elem_ctr:
1369                    break
1370                else:
1371                    j += 1
1372            if j >= num_eb:
1373                raise ValueError("Invalid element number %d in side set %d!" % (elem, obj_id))
1374            if side >= eb_params[j].num_sides:
1375                raise ValueError("Invalid side number %d for element type %s in side set %d!" %
1376                                 (side, eb_params[j].elem_type_str, obj_id))
1377            node_count_list[i] = eb_params[j].num_nodes_per_side[side]
1378        return node_count_list
1379
1380    def get_side_set_node_list(self, obj_id):
1381        """
1382        Returns array of nodes for this side set and the node count list.
1383
1384        :return: (node list, node count list)
1385        """
1386        # Adapted from ex_get_side_set_node_list.c.
1387        # I really really really hope this doesn't have errors in it
1388        internal_id = self._lookup_id(SIDESET, obj_id)
1389        num_eb = self.num_elem_blk
1390        num_elem = self.num_elem
1391        ndim = self.num_dim
1392        num_ss_elem, num_ss_df = self._int_get_side_set_params(obj_id, internal_id)
1393        elem_list, side_list = self.get_side_set(obj_id)
1394        ss_elem_idx = numpy.argsort(elem_list)
1395        eb_id_map = self.get_elem_block_id_map()
1396        eb_params = []
1397        elem_ctr = 0
1398        for i in range(num_eb):
1399            id = eb_id_map[i]
1400            eb_params.append(self._int_get_elem_block_param_object(id, ndim))
1401            elem_ctr += eb_params[i].num_elem_in_blk
1402            eb_params[i].elem_ctr = elem_ctr
1403        ss_param_idx = numpy.empty(num_ss_elem, int)  # ss element to eb param index
1404        ss_elem_node_idx = numpy.empty(num_ss_elem, int)  # ss element to node list index
1405        node_count_list = numpy.empty(num_ss_elem, self.int)
1406        node_ctr = 0
1407        j = 0  # current elem block
1408        for ii in range(num_ss_elem):
1409            i = ss_elem_idx[ii]
1410            elem = elem_list[i]
1411            side = side_list[i]
1412            while j < num_eb:
1413                if eb_params[j].elem_type_val != NULL:
1414                    if elem <= eb_params[j].elem_ctr:
1415                        break
1416                    else:
1417                        j += 1
1418            if j >= num_eb:
1419                raise ValueError("Invalid element number %d in side set %d!" % (elem, obj_id))
1420            if side >= eb_params[j].num_sides:
1421                raise ValueError("Invalid side number %d for element type %s in side set %d!" %
1422                                 (side, eb_params[j].elem_type_str, obj_id))
1423            ss_param_idx[i] = j
1424            ss_elem_node_idx[i] = eb_params[j].num_nodes_per_side[side - 1]
1425            node_ctr += eb_params[j].num_nodes_per_side[side - 1]
1426
1427        if num_ss_df > 0 and num_ss_df != num_ss_elem:
1428            if node_ctr != num_ss_df:
1429                warnings.warn("Side set %d dist fact count (%d) does not match node list length (%d)! This may indicate"
1430                              " a corrupt database." % (obj_id, num_ss_df, node_ctr))
1431
1432        for i in range(num_ss_elem):
1433            node_count_list[i] = ss_elem_node_idx[i]
1434
1435        sum = 0
1436        for i in range(num_ss_elem):
1437            cnt = ss_elem_node_idx[i]
1438            ss_elem_node_idx[i] = sum
1439            sum += cnt
1440
1441        node_list = numpy.empty(node_ctr, self.int)
1442
1443        elem_ctr = 0
1444        connect = None
1445        for j in range(num_ss_elem):
1446            elem_idx = ss_elem_idx[j]
1447            elem = elem_list[elem_idx]
1448            side = side_list[elem_idx]
1449            param_idx = ss_param_idx[elem_idx]
1450
1451            if elem > elem_ctr:
1452                # We're doing this the C way because copying code from SEACAS saves development time
1453                connect = numpy.ndarray.flatten(self.get_elem_block_connectivity(eb_params[param_idx].elem_blk_id))
1454                elem_ctr = eb_params[param_idx].elem_ctr
1455
1456            if connect is None:
1457                raise ValueError("connect is None in get_side_set_node_list. This is likely the result of an abnormal"
1458                                 " Exodus file.")
1459
1460            elem_num = elem - 1
1461            elem_num_pos = elem_num - (eb_params[param_idx].elem_ctr - eb_params[param_idx].num_elem_in_blk)
1462
1463            num_nodes_per_elem = eb_params[param_idx].num_nodes_per_elem
1464            connect_offset = num_nodes_per_elem * elem_num_pos
1465            side_num = side - 1
1466            node_pos = ss_elem_node_idx[elem_idx]
1467
1468            if eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == CIRCLE or eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == SPHERE:
1469                node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset]
1470            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == TRUSS:
1471                node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + side_num]
1472            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == BEAM:
1473                for i in range(num_nodes_per_elem):
1474                    node_list[node_pos + i] = connect[connect_offset + i]
1475            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == TRIANGLE:
1476                if ndim == 2:
1477                    if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 3:
1478                        raise ValueError("Invalid triangle side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1479                    node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + tri_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1480                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + tri_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1481                    if num_nodes_per_elem > 3:
1482                        node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tri_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1483                elif ndim == 3:
1484                    if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 5:
1485                        raise ValueError("Invalid triangle side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1486                    node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1487                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1488                    if side_num + 1 <= 2:
1489                        if num_nodes_per_elem == 3:
1490                            node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1491                        elif num_nodes_per_elem == 4:
1492                            node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1493                            # This looks wrong, but it's what the C library does...
1494                            node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + 4 - 1]
1495                        elif num_nodes_per_elem == 6:
1496                            node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1497                            node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1498                            node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1499                            node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1500                        elif num_nodes_per_elem == 7:
1501                            node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1502                            node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1503                            node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1504                            node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1505                            node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1506                        else:
1507                            raise ValueError("%d is an unsupported number of nodes for triangle elements!" %
1508                                             num_nodes_per_elem)
1509                    else:
1510                        if num_nodes_per_elem > 3:
1511                            node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tri3_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1512            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == QUAD:
1513                if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 4:
1514                    raise ValueError("Invalid quad side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1515                node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + quad_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1516                node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + quad_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1517                if num_nodes_per_elem > 5:
1518                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + quad_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1519            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == SHELL:
1520                if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 6:
1521                    raise ValueError("Invalid shell side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1522                node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1523                node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1524                if num_nodes_per_elem > 2:
1525                    if side_num + 1 <= 2:
1526                        node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1527                        node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1528                if num_nodes_per_elem == 8:
1529                    if side_num + 1 <= 2:
1530                        node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1531                        node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1532                        node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1533                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1534                    else:
1535                        node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1536                if num_nodes_per_elem == 9:
1537                    if side_num + 1 <= 2:
1538                        node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1539                        node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1540                        node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1541                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1542                        node_list[node_pos + 8] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1543                    else:
1544                        node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + shell_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1545            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == TETRA:
1546                if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 4:
1547                    raise ValueError("Invalid tetra side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1548                node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1549                node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1550                node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1551                if num_nodes_per_elem == 8:
1552                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1553                elif num_nodes_per_elem > 8:
1554                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1555                    node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1556                    node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + tetra_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1557            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == WEDGE:
1558                if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 5:
1559                    raise ValueError("Invalid wedge side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1560                if num_nodes_per_elem == 6 or num_nodes_per_elem == 7:
1561                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + wedge6_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1562                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + wedge6_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1563                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + wedge6_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1564                    if side_num == 3 or side_num == 4:
1565                        pass
1566                    else:
1567                        node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + wedge6_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1568                elif num_nodes_per_elem == 15 or num_nodes_per_elem == 16:
1569                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1570                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1571                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1572                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1573                    node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1574                    node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1575                    if side_num == 3 or side_num == 4:
1576                        pass
1577                    else:
1578                        node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1579                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + wedge15_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1580                elif num_nodes_per_elem == 12:
1581                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + wedge12_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1582                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + wedge12_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1583                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + wedge12_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1584                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + wedge12_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1585                    node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + wedge12_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1586                    node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + wedge12_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1587                elif num_nodes_per_elem == 20:
1588                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1589                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1590                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1591                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1592                    node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1593                    node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1594                    node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1595                    if side_num == 3 or side_num == 4:
1596                        pass
1597                    else:
1598                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1599                        node_list[node_pos + 8] = connect[connect_offset + wedge20_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1600                elif num_nodes_per_elem == 21:
1601                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1602                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1603                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1604                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1605                    node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1606                    node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1607                    node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1608                    if side_num == 3 or side_num == 4:
1609                        pass
1610                    else:
1611                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1612                        node_list[node_pos + 8] = connect[connect_offset + wedge21_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1613                elif num_nodes_per_elem == 18:
1614                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1615                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1616                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1617                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1618                    node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1619                    node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1620                    if side_num == 3 or side_num == 4:
1621                        pass
1622                    else:
1623                        node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1624                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1625                        node_list[node_pos + 8] = connect[connect_offset + wedge18_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1626            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == PYRAMID:
1627                if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 5:
1628                    raise ValueError("Invalid pyramid side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1629                node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1630                node_pos += 1
1631                node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1632                node_pos += 1
1633                node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1634                node_pos += 1
1635                if pyramid_table[side_num][3] == 0:
1636                    pass  # this one even confuses the C library
1637                else:
1638                    node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1639                    node_pos += 1
1640                if num_nodes_per_elem > 5:
1641                    node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1642                    node_pos += 1
1643                    node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1644                    node_pos += 1
1645                    node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1646                    node_pos += 1
1647                    if side_num == 4:
1648                        node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1649                        node_pos += 1
1650                        if num_nodes_per_elem >= 14:
1651                            node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1652                            node_pos += 1
1653                    else:
1654                        if num_nodes_per_elem >= 18:
1655                            node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + pyramid_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1656                            node_pos += 1
1657            elif eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_val == HEX:
1658                if side_num + 1 < 1 or side_num + 1 > 6:
1659                    raise ValueError("Invalid hex side number %d!" % (side_num + 1))
1660                if num_nodes_per_elem == 16:
1661                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1662                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1663                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1664                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1665                    # I have no idea whats going on with these next two statements
1666                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1667                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1668                    if side_num + 1 == 5 or side_num + 1 == 6:
1669                        # Also no idea about these ones
1670                        node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1671                        node_pos += 1
1672                        node_list[node_pos] = connect[connect_offset + hex16_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1673                        node_pos += 1
1674                else:
1675                    node_list[node_pos + 0] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][0] - 1]
1676                    node_list[node_pos + 1] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][1] - 1]
1677                    node_list[node_pos + 2] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][2] - 1]
1678                    node_list[node_pos + 3] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][3] - 1]
1679                    if num_nodes_per_elem > 12:
1680                        node_list[node_pos + 4] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][4] - 1]
1681                        node_list[node_pos + 5] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][5] - 1]
1682                        node_list[node_pos + 6] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][6] - 1]
1683                        node_list[node_pos + 7] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][7] - 1]
1684                    if num_nodes_per_elem == 27:
1685                        node_list[node_pos + 8] = connect[connect_offset + hex_table[side_num][8] - 1]
1686            else:
1687                raise ValueError("%s is an unsupported element type." % eb_params[param_idx].elem_type_str)
1688        return node_list, node_count_list

1728    def _int_get_partial_elem_block_connectivity(self, obj_id, internal_id, start, count):
1729        """
1730        Returns a partial connectivity list for the element block with given ID.
1731
1732        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
1733
1734        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
1735        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
1736        :param start: element start index (1-based)
1737        :param count: number of elements
1738        :return: array containing the selected part of the connectivity list
1739        """
1740        if start < 1:
1741            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
1742        if count < 0:
1743            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
1744
1745        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1746            num_node_entry = self.ledger.get_num_nodes_per_el_block(internal_id)
1747        elif (DIM_NUM_NOD_PER_EL % internal_id) in self.data.dimensions:
1748            num_node_entry = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_NOD_PER_EL % internal_id].size
1749        else:
1750            num_node_entry = 0
1751
1752        if num_node_entry > 0:
1753            try:
1754                if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1755                    result = self.ledger.get_connectX(internal_id)[start - 1:start + count - 1]
1756                else:
1757                    result = self.data.variables[VAR_CONNECT % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1]
1758
1759            except KeyError:
1760                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve connectivity list of element block with id {} ('{}')"
1761                               .format(obj_id, VAR_CONNECT % internal_id))
1762        else:
1763            result = []
1764        return result
1765
1766    def _int_get_elem_block_params(self, obj_id, internal_id):
1767        """
1768        Returns a tuple containing the parameters for the element block with given ID.
1769
1770        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY
1771
1772        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
1773        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
1774        :return: (number of elements, nodes per element, topology, number of attributes)
1775        """
1776        # TODO this will be way faster with caching
1777        try:
1778            if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1779                num_entries = self.ledger.get_num_elem_in_block(internal_id)
1780            else:
1781                num_entries = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_EL_IN_BLK % internal_id].size
1782        except KeyError:
1783            raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve number of elements in element block with id {} ('{}')"
1784                           .format(obj_id, DIM_NUM_EL_IN_BLK % internal_id))
1785        
1786        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1787            num_node_entry = self.ledger.get_num_nodes_per_el_block(internal_id)
1788        elif (DIM_NUM_NOD_PER_EL % internal_id) in self.data.dimensions:
1789            num_node_entry = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_NOD_PER_EL % internal_id].size
1790        else:
1791            num_node_entry = 0
1792
1793        try:
1794            if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
1795                topology = self.ledger.get_elem_block_type(internal_id)
1796            if num_node_entry > 0:
1797                connect = self.data.variables[VAR_CONNECT % internal_id]
1798                topology = connect.getncattr(ATTR_ELEM_TYPE)
1799            else:
1800                topology = None
1801        except KeyError:
1802            raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve connectivity list of element block with id {} ('{}')"
1803                           .format(obj_id, VAR_CONNECT % internal_id))
1804        
1805	# TODO: Add case for append mode if attributes added
1806        if (DIM_NUM_ATT_IN_BLK % internal_id) in self.data.dimensions:
1807            num_att_blk = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_ATT_IN_BLK % internal_id].size
1808        else:
1809            num_att_blk = 0
1810        return num_entries, num_node_entry, topology, num_att_blk
1811

1836    def _int_get_elem_block_param_object(self, obj_id, ndim) -> _ElemBlockParam:
1837        """Returns parameters used to describe an elem block."""
1838        # Adapted from ex_int_get_block_param.c
1839        # Used to get side set node count list
1840        num_el, nod_el, topo, num_att = self.get_elem_block_params(obj_id)
1841        topo = topo.upper()
1842        num_nod_side = numpy.zeros(6, builtins.int)
1843        if topo[:3] == CIRCLE[:3]:
1844            el_type = CIRCLE
1845            num_sides = 1
1846            num_nod_side[0] = 1
1847        elif topo[:3] == SPHERE[:3]:
1848            el_type = SPHERE
1849            num_sides = 1
1850            num_nod_side[0] = 1
1851        elif topo[:3] == QUAD[:3]:
1852            el_type = QUAD
1853            num_sides = 4
1854            if nod_el == 4 or nod_el == 5:
1855                num_nod_side[0] = 2
1856                num_nod_side[1] = 2
1857                num_nod_side[2] = 2
1858                num_nod_side[3] = 2
1859            elif nod_el == 9 or nod_el == 8:
1860                num_nod_side[0] = 3
1861                num_nod_side[1] = 3
1862                num_nod_side[2] = 3
1863                num_nod_side[3] = 3
1864            elif nod_el == 12 or nod_el == 16:
1865                num_nod_side[0] = 4
1866                num_nod_side[1] = 4
1867                num_nod_side[2] = 4
1868                num_nod_side[3] = 4
1869            else:
1870                raise ValueError("Element of type %s with %d nodes is invalid!" % (topo, nod_el))
1871        elif topo[:3] == TRIANGLE[:3]:
1872            el_type = TRIANGLE
1873            if ndim == 2:
1874                num_sides = 3
1875                if nod_el == 3 or nod_el == 4:
1876                    num_nod_side[0] = 2
1877                    num_nod_side[1] = 2
1878                    num_nod_side[2] = 2
1879                elif nod_el == 6 or nod_el == 7:
1880                    num_nod_side[0] = 3
1881                    num_nod_side[1] = 3
1882                    num_nod_side[2] = 3
1883                elif nod_el == 9 or nod_el == 13:
1884                    num_nod_side[0] = 4
1885                    num_nod_side[1] = 4
1886                    num_nod_side[2] = 4
1887                else:
1888                    raise ValueError("Element of type %s with %d nodes is invalid!" % (topo, nod_el))
1889            elif ndim == 3:
1890                num_sides = 5
1891                if nod_el == 3 or nod_el == 4:
1892                    num_nod_side[0] = nod_el
1893                    num_nod_side[1] = nod_el
1894                    num_nod_side[2] = 2
1895                    num_nod_side[3] = 2
1896                    num_nod_side[4] = 2
1897                elif nod_el == 6 or nod_el == 7:
1898                    num_nod_side[0] = nod_el
1899                    num_nod_side[1] = nod_el
1900                    num_nod_side[2] = 3
1901                    num_nod_side[3] = 3
1902                    num_nod_side[4] = 3
1903                elif nod_el == 9 or nod_el == 13:
1904                    num_nod_side[0] = nod_el
1905                    num_nod_side[1] = nod_el
1906                    num_nod_side[2] = 4
1907                    num_nod_side[3] = 4
1908                    num_nod_side[4] = 4
1909                else:
1910                    raise ValueError("Element of type %s with %d nodes is invalid!" % (topo, nod_el))
1911        elif topo[:3] == SHELL[:3]:
1912            el_type = SHELL
1913            if nod_el == 2:
1914                num_sides = 2
1915                num_nod_side[0] = 2
1916                num_nod_side[1] = 2
1917            elif nod_el == 4:
1918                num_sides = 6
1919                num_nod_side[0] = 4
1920                num_nod_side[1] = 4
1921                num_nod_side[2] = 2
1922                num_nod_side[3] = 2
1923                num_nod_side[4] = 2
1924                num_nod_side[5] = 2
1925            elif nod_el == 8 or nod_el == 9:
1926                num_sides = 6
1927                num_nod_side[0] = nod_el
1928                num_nod_side[1] = nod_el
1929                num_nod_side[2] = 3
1930                num_nod_side[3] = 3
1931                num_nod_side[4] = 3
1932                num_nod_side[5] = 3
1933            else:
1934                raise ValueError("Element of type %s with %d nodes is invalid!" % (topo, nod_el))
1935        elif topo[:3] == HEX[:3]:
1936            el_type = HEX
1937            num_sides = 6
1938            if nod_el == 8 or nod_el == 9:

2119                num_nod_side[1] = 1
2120            else:
2121                raise ValueError("Element of type %s with %d nodes is invalid!" % (topo, nod_el))
2122        # Special case for null elements
2123        elif topo[:3] == NULL[:3]:
2124            el_type = NULL
2125            num_sides = 0
2126            num_nod_side[0] = 0
2127            num_el = 0
2128        else:
2129            el_type = UNKNOWN
2130            num_sides = 0
2131            num_nod_side[0] = 0
2132        return _ElemBlockParam(topo, obj_id, num_el, nod_el, num_sides, num_nod_side, num_att, 0, el_type)

2138    def _get_set_block_names(self, obj_type: ObjectType):
2139        """
2140        Returns a list of names for objects of a given type.
2141        :param obj_type: type of object
2142        :return: a list of names
2143        """
2144        names = []
2145        if obj_type == NODESET:
2146            try:
2147                names = self.data.variables[VAR_NS_NAMES]
2148            except KeyError:
2149                warnings.warn("This database does not contain node set names.")
2150        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
2151            try:
2152                names = self.data.variables[VAR_SS_NAMES]
2153            except KeyError:
2154                warnings.warn("This database does not contain side set names.")
2155        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
2156            try:
2157                names = self.data.variables[VAR_EB_NAMES]
2158            except KeyError:
2159                warnings.warn("This database does not contain element block names.")
2160        else:
2161            raise ValueError("{} is not a valid set/block type!".format(obj_type))
2162        result = numpy.empty([len(names)], self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2163        for i in range(len(names)):
2164            result[i] = util.lineparse(names[i])
2165        return result
2166
2167    def get_elem_block_names(self):
2168        """Returns an array containing the names of element blocks in this database."""
2169        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
2170            return self.ledger.get_elem_block_names()
2171        return self._get_set_block_names(ELEMBLOCK)
2172
2173    def get_elem_block_name(self, obj_id):
2174        """Returns the name of the given element block."""
2175        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
2176            return self.ledger.get_elem_block_name(obj_id)
2177        
2178        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
2179        names = self._get_set_block_names(ELEMBLOCK)
2180
2181        if len(names) > 0:
2182            return names[internal_id - 1]
2183        else:
2184            return None

2223    def _int_get_num_elem_attrib(self, internal_id):
2224        """
2225        Returns the number of attributes in the element block with given internal ID.
2226
2227        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY!
2228        """
2229        # Some databases don't have attributes
2230        if (DIM_NUM_ATT_IN_BLK % internal_id) in self.data.dimensions:
2231            num = self.data.dimensions[DIM_NUM_ATT_IN_BLK % internal_id].size
2232        else:
2233            # No need to warn. If there are no attributes, the number is 0...
2234            num = 0
2235        return num
2236
2237    def _int_get_partial_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, internal_id, start, count):
2238        """
2239        Returns a partial list of all attributes for the element block with given ID.
2240
2241        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2242
2243        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY
2244
2245        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
2246        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
2247        :param start: element start index (1-based)
2248        :param count: number of elements
2249        :return: array containing the selected part of the attribute list
2250        """
2251        if start < 1:
2252            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2253        if count < 0:
2254            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2255        varname = VAR_ELEM_ATTRIB % internal_id
2256        if varname in self.data.variables:
2257            result = self.data.variables[varname][start - 1:start + count - 1, :]
2258        else:
2259            result = []
2260            warnings.warn("Element block {} has no attributes.".format(obj_id))
2261        return result
2262
2263    def _int_get_partial_one_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, internal_id, attrib_index, start, count):
2264        """
2265        Returns a partial list of one attribute for the element block with given ID.
2266
2267        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2268
2269        FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY
2270
2271        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
2272        :param internal_id: INTERNAL (1-based) id
2273        :param attrib_index: attribute index (1-based)
2274        :param start: element start index (1-based)
2275        :param count: number of elements
2276        :return: array containing the selected part of the attribute list
2277        """
2278        if start < 1:
2279            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2280        if count < 0:
2281            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2282        num_attrib = self._int_get_num_elem_attrib(internal_id)
2283        if num_attrib > 0:  # faster to check this than if the variable exists like in the function above this one
2284            if attrib_index < 1 or attrib_index > num_attrib:
2285                raise ValueError("Attribute index out of range. Got {}".format(attrib_index))
2286            result = self.data.variables[VAR_ELEM_ATTRIB % internal_id][start - 1:start + count - 1, attrib_index - 1]
2287        else:
2288            result = []
2289            warnings.warn("Element block {} has no attributes.".format(obj_id))
2290        return result
2291
2292    def get_partial_one_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, attrib_index, start, count):
2293        """
2294        Returns a partial list of one attribute for the specified elements in the element block with given ID.
2295
2296        Array starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
2297        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2298        """
2299        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
2300        return self._int_get_partial_one_elem_attrib(obj_id, internal_id, attrib_index, start, count)
2301
2302    def get_one_elem_attrib(self, obj_id, attrib_index):
2303        """
2304        Returns a list of one attribute for each element in the element block with given ID.
2305
2306        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes.
2307        """

2309        size = self._int_get_elem_block_params(obj_id, internal_id)[0]
2310        return self._int_get_partial_one_elem_attrib(obj_id, internal_id, attrib_index, 1, size)

2332    def get_elem_attrib_names(self, obj_id):
2333        """
2334        Returns a list of the names of attributes in the element block with given ID.
2335
2336        Returns an empty array if the element block doesn't have attributes or attribute names.
2337        """
2338        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
2339        num_attrib = self._int_get_num_elem_attrib(internal_id)
2340        result = []
2341        if num_attrib == 0:
2342            warnings.warn("Element block {} has no attributes.".format(obj_id))
2343        else:
2344            varname = VAR_ELEM_ATTRIB_NAME % internal_id
2345            # Older datasets don't have attribute names
2346            if varname in self.data.variables:
2347                names = self.data.variables[varname][:]
2348                result = util.arrparse(names, len(names), self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2349            else:
2350                warnings.warn("Attributes of element block {} have no names.".format(obj_id))
2351        return result

2359    # Object properties #

2361
2362    # This method contains a general algorithm for counting the number of properties an object has.
2363    # This is used by the num_*_prop properties which are in turn used by _get_object_property_names
2364    def _get_num_object_properties(self, varname):
2365        """
2366        Returns the number of properties an object has.
2367
2368        :param varname: the netCDF variable name of the property. ("xx_prop_%d") where xx is ns, ss, or eb
2369        :return: number of properties
2370        """
2371        # loop over the prop variables and count how many there are
2372        n = 0
2373        while True:
2374            if varname % (n + 1) in self.data.variables:
2375                n += 1
2376            else:
2377                break
2378        return n
2379
2380    def _get_object_property(self, obj_type: ObjectType, obj_id, name):
2381        """
2382        Returns the value of a specific object's property.
2383
2384        :param obj_type: type of object this id refers to
2385        :param obj_id: EXTERNAL (user-defined) id
2386        :param name: name of the property
2387        :return: value of the property for the specified object
2388        """
2389        internal_id = self._lookup_id(obj_type, obj_id)
2390        prop = self._get_object_property_array(obj_type, name)
2391        # We don't want to index into prop if it's empty
2392        if len(prop) > 0:
2393            return prop[internal_id - 1]
2394        else:
2395            return None
2396
2397    def get_node_set_property(self, obj_id, name):
2398        """Returns the value of the specified property for the node set with the given ID."""
2399        return self._get_object_property(NODESET, obj_id, name)

2408
2409    def _get_object_property_array(self, obj_type: ObjectType, name):
2410        """
2411        Returns a list containing all the values of a particular property for objects of a given type.
2412
2413        :param obj_type: type of object this id refers to
2414        :param name: name of the property
2415        :return: array containing values of the property for objects of the given type
2416        """
2417        if obj_type == NODESET:
2418            varname = VAR_NS_PROP
2419        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
2420            varname = VAR_SS_PROP
2421        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
2422            varname = VAR_EB_PROP
2423        else:
2424            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(obj_type))
2425        prop = []
2426        # Search for the property for the right name
2427        # We don't use a for loop over the number of props because that would cost a second loop over the props
2428        n = 1
2429        while True:
2430            if varname % n in self.data.variables:
2431                propname = self.data.variables[varname % n].getncattr(ATTR_NAME)
2432                if propname == name:
2433                    # we've found our property
2434                    prop = self.data.variables[varname % n][:]
2435                    break
2436                else:
2437                    # check next property
2438                    n += 1
2439                    continue
2440            else:
2441                # "xx_prop_n" doesn't exist. name doesn't exist in file
2442                warnings.warn("Property {} does not exist!".format(name))
2443                break
2444        return prop
2445
2446    def get_node_set_property_array(self, name):
2447        """Returns a list containing the values of the specified property for all node sets."""
2448        return self._get_object_property_array(NODESET, name)
2449
2450    def get_side_set_property_array(self, name):
2451        """Returns a list containing the values of the specified property for all side sets."""
2452        return self._get_object_property_array(SIDESET, name)
2453
2454    def get_elem_block_property_array(self, name):
2455        """Returns a list containing the values of the specified property for all element blocks."""
2456        return self._get_object_property_array(ELEMBLOCK, name)
2457
2458    def _get_object_property_names(self, obj_type: ObjectType):
2459        """
2460        Returns a list containing the names of properties defined for objects of a given type.
2461
2462        :param obj_type: type of object
2463        :return: array of property names
2464        """
2465        if obj_type == NODESET:
2466            varname = VAR_NS_PROP
2467            num_props = self.num_node_set_prop
2468        elif obj_type == SIDESET:
2469            varname = VAR_SS_PROP
2470            num_props = self.num_side_set_prop
2471        elif obj_type == ELEMBLOCK:
2472            varname = VAR_EB_PROP
2473            num_props = self.num_elem_block_prop
2474        else:
2475            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(obj_type))
2476        # num_props = self._get_num_object_properties(varname)
2477        result = numpy.empty([num_props], self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2478        for n in range(num_props):
2479            result[n] = self.data.variables[varname % (n + 1)].getncattr(ATTR_NAME)
2480        return result
2481
2482    def get_node_set_property_names(self):
2483        """Returns a list of node set property names."""
2484        return self._get_object_property_names(NODESET)

2491        """Returns a list of element block property names."""
2492        return self._get_object_property_names(ELEMBLOCK)

2498    def get_coords(self):
2499        """Returns a multidimensional array containing the coordinates of all nodes."""
2500        # Technically this incurs an extra call to num_nodes, but the reduced complexity is worth it
2501        return self.get_partial_coords(1, self.num_nodes)
2502
2503    def get_partial_coords(self, start, count):
2504        """
2505        Returns a multidimensional array containing the coordinates of the specified set of nodes.
2506
2507        Array starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
2508        """
2509        if start < 1:
2510            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2511        if count < 0:
2512            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2513        dim_cnt = self.num_dim
2514        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
2515        if num_nodes == 0:
2516            return []
2517        large = self.large_model
2518        if not large:
2519            try:
2520                coord = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD][:, start - 1:start + count - 1]
2521            except KeyError:
2522                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve nodal coordinate array!")
2523        else:
2524            try:
2525                coordx = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_X][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2526            except KeyError:
2527                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve x axis nodal coordinate array!")
2528            if dim_cnt > 1:
2529                try:
2530                    coordy = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_Y][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2531                except KeyError:
2532                    raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve y axis nodal coordinate array!")
2533                if dim_cnt > 2:
2534                    try:
2535                        coordz = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_Z][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2536                    except KeyError:
2537                        raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve z axis nodal coordinate array!")
2538                    coord = numpy.array([coordx, coordy, coordz])
2539                else:
2540                    coord = numpy.array([coordx, coordy])
2541            else:
2542                coord = coordx
2543        return coord
2544
2545    def get_coord_x(self):
2546        """Returns an array containing the x coordinate of all nodes."""
2547        return self.get_partial_coord_x(1, self.num_nodes)
2548
2549    def get_partial_coord_x(self, start, count):
2550        """
2551        Returns an array containing the x coordinate of the specified set of nodes.
2552
2553        Array starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
2554        """
2555        if start < 1:
2556            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
2557        if count < 0:
2558            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
2559        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
2560        if num_nodes == 0:
2561            return []
2562        large = self.large_model
2563        if not large:
2564            try:
2565                coord = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD][0][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2566            except KeyError:
2567                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve nodal coordinate array!")
2568        else:
2569            try:
2570                coord = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_X][start - 1:start + count - 1]
2571            except KeyError:
2572                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve x axis nodal coordinate array!")
2573        return coord

2637    def get_coord_names(self):
2638        """Returns an array containing the names of the coordinate axes in this database."""
2639        dim_cnt = self.num_dim
2640        try:
2641            names = self.data.variables[VAR_COORD_NAMES]
2642        except KeyError:
2643            raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve coordinate name array!")
2644        result = util.arrparse(names, dim_cnt, self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T)
2645        return result

2647    ################
2648    # File records #
2649    ################
2650
2651    def get_info(self):
2652        """Returns an array containing the info records stored in this database."""
2653        num = self.num_info
2654        result = numpy.empty([num], Exodus._MAX_LINE_LENGTH_T)
2655        if num > 0:
2656            try:
2657                infos = self.data.variables[VAR_INFO]
2658            except KeyError:
2659                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve info records from database!")
2660            for i in range(num):
2661                result[i] = util.lineparse(infos[i])
2662        return result
2663
2664    def get_qa(self):
2665        """Returns an n x 4 array containing the QA records stored in this database."""
2666        num = self.num_qa
2667        result = numpy.empty([num, 4], Exodus._MAX_STR_LENGTH_T)
2668        if num > 0:
2669            try:
2670                qas = self.data.variables[VAR_QA]
2671            except KeyError:
2672                raise KeyError("Failed to retrieve qa records from database!")
2673            for i in range(num):
2674                for j in range(4):
2675                    result[i, j] = util.lineparse(qas[i, j])
2676        return result

2690    def time_steps(self):
2691        """Returns list of the time steps, 0-indexed"""
2692        return [*range(self.num_time_steps)]
2693
2694    def step_at_time(self, time):
2695        """Given a float time value, return the corresponding time step"""
2696        for index, value in enumerate(self.get_all_times()):
2697            if value == time:
2698                return index
2699        return None

2701    # TODO remove?
2702    def set_nodeset(self, node_set_id, node_ids):
2703        ndx = node_set_id - 1
2704        if "ns_prop1" in self.data.variables:
2705            ndx = numpy.where(self.data.variables["ns_prop1"][:] == node_set_id)[0][0]
2706            ndx += 1
2707
2708        key = "node_ns" + str(ndx)
2709        nodeset = self.data[key]
2710
2711        if "node_num_map" in self.data.variables:
2712            indices = numpy.zeros(len(node_ids))
2713            i = 0
2714            for id in node_ids:
2715                ndx = numpy.where(self.data["node_num_map"][:] == id)[0][0]
2716                indices[i] = ndx
2717                i += 1
2718            nodeset[:] = indices
2719            return
2720        nodeset[:] = node_ids
2721
2722    # TODO remove?
2723    def get_nodes_in_elblock(self, id):
2724        if self.mode == 'w' or self.mode == 'a':
2725            return self.ledger.get_connectX(id)
2726
2727        if "node_num_map" in self.data.variables:
2728            raise Exception("Using node num map")
2729        nodeids = self.data["connect" + str(id)]
2730        # flatten it into 1d
2731        nodeids = nodeids[:].flatten()
2732        return nodeids

2739
2740    def diff(self, other):
2741        # # Nodesets
2742        selfNS = self.num_node_sets
2743        otherNS = other.num_node_sets
2744        print("Self # Nodesets:\t{}".format(selfNS))
2745        print("Other # Nodesets:\t{}".format(otherNS))
2746
2747        # # Sidesets
2748        selfSS = self.num_side_sets
2749        otherSS = other.num_side_sets
2750        print("\nSelf # Sidesets:\t{}".format(selfSS))
2751        print("Other # Sidesets:\t{}".format(otherSS))
2752
2753        # # Nodes
2754        selfN = self.num_nodes
2755        otherN = other.num_nodes
2756        print("\nSelf # Nodes:\t\t{}".format(selfN))
2757        print("Other # Nodes:\t\t{}".format(otherN))
2758
2759        # # Elements
2760        selfE = self.num_elem
2761        otherE = other.num_elem
2762        print("\nSelf # Elements:\t{}".format(selfE))
2763        print("Other # Elements:\t{}\n".format(otherE))
2764
2765        # Length of output variables (nodal/elemental)
2766
2767    def diff_nodeset(self, id, other, id2=None):
2768        """
2769        Prints the overlap and difference between two nodesets
2770        :param id: the nodeset ID of the self Exodus object
2771        :param other: the other Exodus object to compare to
2772        :param id2: optional parameter specifying the nodeset ID of other Exodus object. Default to the first id.
2773        """
2774
2775        if other is None:
2776            raise ValueError("Other Exodus file is None")
2777
2778        if id2 is None:
2779            id2 = id
2780        try:
2781            ns1 = self.get_node_set(id)
2782        except KeyError:
2783            raise KeyError("Self Exodus file does not contain nodeset with ID {}".format(id))
2784
2785        try:
2786            ns2 = other.get_node_set(id2)
2787        except KeyError:
2788            raise KeyError("Other Exodus file does not contain nodeset with ID {}".format(id2))
2789
2790        equivalent = numpy.array_equal(numpy.array(sorted(ns1.tolist())), numpy.array(sorted(ns2.tolist())))
2791        if equivalent:
2792            print("Self NS {} contains the same Node IDs as Other NS ID {}".format(id, id2))
2793        else:
2794            print("Self NS ID {} does NOT contain the same nodes as Other NS ID {}".format(id, id2))
2795            intersection = set(ns1) & set(ns2)
2796            print("\tBoth nodesets share the following nodes:\n\t{}".format(sorted(list(intersection))))
2797            ns1_diff = sorted(list(set(ns1) - intersection))
2798            print("\tSelf NS ID {} also contains nodes:\n\t{}".format(id, ns1_diff))
2799            ns2_diff = sorted(list(set(ns2) - intersection))
2800            print("\tOther NS ID {} also contains nodes:\n\t{}\n".format(id2, ns2_diff))

3002    def write(self, path=None):
3003        if self.mode != 'w' and self.mode != 'a':
3004            raise PermissionError("Need to be in write or append mode to write")
3005        elif self.mode == 'a' and path is None:
3006            raise AttributeError("Must specify a new path when in append mode")
3007        elif self.mode == 'w' and path is not None:
3008            raise AttributeError("Do not specify a new path in write mode. Initialization path will be used")
3009        self.ledger.write(path)

The Exodus class represents an opened Exodus II file.

The first step in doing anything to an Exodus II file is to create a new Exodus object from it (See Exodus.__init__ for how to do this).

You can read and modify an Exodus II file using Exodus's properties and functions. You may not modify properties, but you can get them with minimal performance impact. Calling any functions will read data from the file on disk, and this data is not cached by the library, so you should avoid multiple identical function calls whenever possible.

Many of the functions of Exodus require "1-based" indices. To clarify: Exodus data is usually accessed starting from 1 rather than 0 as is more common in computer programming. If a function requests 1-based indices that means list indexing starts at 1. If a function requests 0-based indices that means list indexing starts at 0.

Once you are finished with the Exodus II file, call Exodus.close to safely close the file.

#   Exodus(path, mode, shared=False, format='EX_NETCDF4', word_size=4)
View Source 
 63    def __init__(self, path, mode, shared=False, format='EX_NETCDF4', word_size=4):
 64        """
 65        Exodus constructor.
 66
 67        :param path: path to the Exodus II file to open as a string.
 68        :param mode: access mode. 'r' opens the file in read only mode. 'a' is append mode; it allows you to modify the
 69        file as well as read from it. 'w' is write mode; it creates a new file at the specified path and opens it as in
 70        append mode.
 71        :param shared: if `True` the file will open with unbuffered shared access for NetCDF 3 classic, 64bit offset,
 72        and 64bit data models (EX_NORMAL_MODEL, EX_LARGE_MODEL, EX_64BIT_DATA).
 73        :param format: if `mode` is 'w' then this is the underlying netCDF format the database will use.
 74        :param word_size: if `mode` is 'w' then this is the floating point word size used in the database.
 75        """
 76        # clobber and format and word_size only apply to mode w
 77        if mode not in ['r', 'w', 'a']:
 78            raise ValueError("mode must be 'w', 'r', or 'a', got '{}'".format(mode))
 79        if format not in Exodus._FORMAT_MAP.keys():
 80            raise ValueError("invalid file format: '{}'".format(format))
 81        if word_size not in [4, 8]:
 82            raise ValueError("word_size must be 4 or 8 bytes, {} is not supported".format(word_size))
 83        nc_format = Exodus._FORMAT_MAP[format]
 84
 85        self.mode = mode
 86        self.path = path
 87
 88        # file should never actually be opened in append mode
 89        # if append mode is specified, open file in read mode and write out changes to separate file
 90        if mode == 'a':
 91            mode = 'r'
 92
 93        # Sets shared mode if the user asked for it. I have no idea what this does :)
 94        if shared:
 95            smode = mode + 's'
 96        else:
 97            smode = mode
 98        try:
 99            self.data = nc.Dataset(path, smode, clobber=False, format=nc_format)
100        except FileNotFoundError:
101            raise FileNotFoundError("file '{}' does not exist".format(path)) from None
102        except PermissionError:
103            raise PermissionError("You do not have access to '{}'".format(path)) from None
104        # this can actually hide some errors which is bad.
105        # except OSError:
106        #     raise OSError("file '{}' already exists".format(path)) from None
107
108        if self.mode == 'w':
109            # This is important according to ex_open.c
110            self.data.set_fill_off()
111
112        if self.mode == 'a' or self.mode == 'w':
113            self.ledger = Ledger(self)
114
115        # save path variable for future use
116        self.path = path
117
118        # We will read a bunch of data here to make sure it exists and warn the user if they might want to fix their
119        # file. We don't save anything to memory so that if our data updates we don't have to update it in memory too.
120        # This is the same practice used in the C library so its probably a good idea.
121
122        # Initialize all the important parameters
123        if mode == 'w':
124            self.data.setncattr('title', 'Untitled database')
125            self.data.createDimension('len_string', Exodus._MAX_STR_LENGTH + 1)
126            self.data.createDimension('len_name', Exodus._MAX_NAME_LENGTH + 1)
127            self.data.createDimension('len_line', Exodus._MAX_LINE_LENGTH + 1)
128            self.data.setncattr('maximum_name_length', Exodus._MAX_NAME_LENGTH)
129            self.data.setncattr('version', Exodus._EXODUS_VERSION)
130            self.data.setncattr('api_version', Exodus._EXODUS_VERSION)
131            self.data.setncattr('floating_point_word_size', word_size)
132            file_size = 0
133            if nc_format == 'NETCDF3_64BIT_OFFSET':
134                file_size = 1
135            self.data.setncattr('file_size', file_size)
136            int64bit_status = 0
137            if nc_format == 'NETCDF3_64BIT_DATA':
138                int64bit_status = 1
139            self.data.setncattr('int64_status', int64bit_status)
140
141        # Check version compatibility
142        ver = self.version
143        if ver < 2.0:
144            raise RuntimeError(
145                "Unsupported file version {:.2f}! Only versions >2.0 are supported.".format(ver))
146
147        # Read word size stored in file
148        ws = self.word_size
149        if ws == 4:
150            self._float = numpy.float32
151        elif ws == 8:
152            self._float = numpy.float64
153        else:
154            raise ValueError("file contains a word size of {} which is not supported".format(ws))
155
156        if self.int64_status == 0:
157            self._int = numpy.int32
158        else:
159            self._int = numpy.int64
160
161        # important for storing names in numpy arrays
162        self._MAX_NAME_LENGTH_T = 'U%s' % self.max_allowed_name_length

  • word_size: if mode is 'w' then this is the floating point word size used in the database.

484    def get_elem_order_map(self):

#   def get_partial_node_id_map(self, start, count):
View Source 
531    def get_partial_node_id_map(self, start, count):
532        """
533        Return a subset of the node ID map for this database.
534
535        Subset starts at node number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
536        """
537        # Start is 1 based (>0).  start + count - 1 <= number of nodes
538        num_nodes = self.num_nodes
539        if num_nodes == 0:
540            raise KeyError("Cannot retrieve a node id map if there are no nodes!")
541        if start < 1:
542            raise ValueError("start index must be greater than 0")
543        if start + count - 1 > num_nodes:
544            raise ValueError("start index + node count is larger than the total number of nodes")
545        if VAR_NODE_ID_MAP not in self.data.variables:
546            # Return a default array from start to start + count exclusive
547            warnings.warn("There is no node id map in this database!")
548            return numpy.arange(start, start + count, dtype=self.int)
549        return self.data.variables[VAR_NODE_ID_MAP][start - 1:start + count - 1]

Return a subset of the node ID map for this database.

Subset starts at node number start (1-based) and contains count elements.

#   def get_elem_id_map_for_block(self, obj_id):

587    def get_elem_id_map_for_block(self, obj_id):
588        """Reads the element ID map for the element block with specified ID."""
589        if self.num_elem_blk == 0:
590            raise KeyError("There are no element blocks in this database!")
591        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
592        num_elem, _, _, _ = self._int_get_elem_block_params(obj_id, internal_id)
593        offset = 0
594        emap = self.get_elem_id_map()
595        for i in range(1, internal_id):
596            n, _, _, _ = self._int_get_elem_block_params(emap[i - 1], i)
597            offset += n
598        return self.get_partial_elem_id_map(offset + 1, num_elem)

Reads the element ID map for the element block with specified ID.

703    def get_time(self, time_step):
704        """
705        Returns the time value for specified time step.
706
707        Time steps are 1-indexed. The first time step is at 1, and the last at num_time_steps.
708        """
709        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
710        if num_steps <= 0:
711            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
712        if time_step <= 0 or time_step > num_steps:
713            raise ValueError("Time step out of range. Got {}".format(time_step))
714        return self.get_all_times()[time_step - 1]

Returns the time value for specified time step.

#   def get_partial_nodal_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index, start_index, count):
View Source 
732    def get_partial_nodal_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index, start_index, count):
733        """
734        Returns partial values of a nodal variable between specified time steps (inclusive).
735
736        Time steps, variable index, ID and start index are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
737        Array starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.
738        """
739        if self.num_nodes == 0:
740            return [[]]
741        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
742        if num_steps <= 0:
743            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
744        if start_time_step <= 0 or start_time_step > num_steps:
745            raise ValueError("Start time step out of range. Got {}".format(start_time_step))
746        if end_time_step <= 0 or end_time_step < start_time_step or end_time_step > num_steps:
747            raise ValueError("End time step out of range. Got {}".format(end_time_step))
748        if var_index <= 0 or var_index > self.num_node_var:
749            raise ValueError("Variable index out of range. Got {}".format(var_index))
750        if start_index <= 0:
751            raise ValueError("Start index must be greater than 0")
752        if count < 0:
753            raise ValueError("Count must be a positive integer")
754        if not self.large_model:
755            # All vars stored in one variable
756            try:
757                # Do not subtract 1 from end (inclusive)
758                result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_NOD_VAR_SMALL][
759                         start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, var_index - 1, start_index - 1:start_index + count - 1]
760            except KeyError:
761                raise KeyError("Could not find the nodal variables in this database!")
762        else:
763            # Each var to its own variable
764            try:
765                result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_NOD_VAR_LARGE % var_index][start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, :]
766            except KeyError:
767                raise KeyError("Could not find nodal variable {} in this database!".format(var_index))
768        return result

Returns partial values of a nodal variable between specified time steps (inclusive).

Time steps, variable index, ID and start index are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps. Array starts at element number start (1-based) and contains count elements.

#   def get_global_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
View Source 
806    def get_global_var_across_times(self, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
807        """
808        Returns the values of the global variable with given index between specified time steps (inclusive).
809
810        Time steps and variable index are both 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
811        """
812        num_steps = self.num_time_steps
813        if num_steps <= 0:
814            raise ValueError("There are no time steps in this database!")
815        if start_time_step <= 0 or start_time_step > num_steps:
816            raise ValueError("Time step out of range. Got {}".format(start_time_step))
817        if end_time_step <= 0 or end_time_step < start_time_step or end_time_step > num_steps:
818            raise ValueError("End time step out of range. Got {}".format(end_time_step))
819        if var_index <= 0 or var_index > self.num_global_var:
820            raise ValueError("Variable index out of range. Got {}".format(var_index))
821        try:
822            result = self.data.variables[VAR_VALS_GLO_VAR][start_time_step - 1:end_time_step, var_index - 1]
823        except KeyError:
824            raise KeyError("Could not find global variables in this database!")
825        return result

Returns the values of the global variable with given index between specified time steps (inclusive).

Time steps and variable index are both 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.

Returns the values of variable with index stored in the element block with id at time step.

#   def get_elem_block_var_across_times(self, obj_id, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
View Source 
886    def get_elem_block_var_across_times(self, obj_id, start_time_step, end_time_step, var_index):
887        """
888        Returns the values of variable with index stored in the element block with id between time steps (inclusive).
889
890        Time steps, variable index, and ID are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.
891        """
892        # This method cannot simply call its partial version because we cannot know the number of elements to read
893        #  without looking up the id first. This extra id lookup call is slow, so we get around it with a helper method.
894        internal_id = self._lookup_id(ELEMBLOCK, obj_id)
895        size = self._int_get_elem_block_params(obj_id, internal_id)[0]
896        return self._int_get_partial_object_var_across_times(ELEMBLOCK, internal_id, start_time_step, end_time_step,
897                                                             var_index, 1, size)

Returns the values of variable with index stored in the element block with id between time steps (inclusive).

Time steps, variable index, and ID are all 1-based. First time step is at 1, last at num_time_steps.

900                                                count):
901        """
902        Returns partial values of an element block variable between specified time steps (inclusive).
903

905        Array starts at element number ``start`` (1-based) and contains ``count`` elements.

908        return self._int_get_partial_object_var_across_times(ELEMBLOCK, internal_id, start_time_step, end_time_step,
909                                                             var_index, start_index, count)

#   def has_var_names(self, var_type: <function NewType.<locals>.new_type>):
View Source 
1050    def has_var_names(self, var_type: VariableType):
1051        """
1052        Test if this Exodus file has variable names for a variable type.
1053
1054        :param var_type: GLOBAL_VAR, NODAL_VAR, ELEMENTAL_VAR, NODESET_VAR, or SIDESET_VAR from `exodusutils.constants`
1055        :return: True if this variable type has names defined, false otherwise
1056        """
1057        if var_type == GLOBAL_VAR:
1058            varname = VAR_NAME_GLO_VAR
1059        elif var_type == NODAL_VAR:
1060            varname = VAR_NAME_NOD_VAR
1061        elif var_type == ELEMENTAL_VAR:
1062            varname = VAR_NAME_ELEM_VAR
1063        elif var_type == NODESET_VAR:
1064            varname = VAR_NAME_NS_VAR
1065        elif var_type == SIDESET_VAR:
1066            varname = VAR_NAME_SS_VAR
1067        else:
1068            raise ValueError("Invalid variable type {}!".format(var_type))
1069        return varname in self.data.variables

Test if this Exodus file has variable names for a variable type.

Parameters
  • var_type: GLOBAL_VAR, NODAL_VAR, ELEMENTAL_VAR, NODESET_VAR, or SIDESET_VAR from exodusutils.constants
Returns

True if this variable type has names defined, false otherwise
